<FIRST>r w PM-RefugeeDetention     02-17 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Refugee Detention,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Plans To Detain Refugees In Tent City</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department plans to detain Central
American refugees in a ``tent city'' on isolated South Texas
brushland while their applications for political asylum are
processed, congressional officials say.
   Immigration and Naturalization Service spokesman Duke Austin said
Thursday that there had been ``no public disclosure'' of the Bush
administration's plans for handling the flood of refugees and that
the issue was still under review.
   But Capitol Hill officials disclosed the Justice Department plan
to pitch tents on land adjacent to a minimum-security federal
detention center now being used to process the refugees'
applications.
   Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, said in a statement that the tent camp
would meet basic human necessities of adequate housing, food and
sanitary conditions.
   More than 2,000 refugees from Central America are crossing into
the United States illegally every week, most of them coming across
the Rio Grande at Brownsville from Mexico, officials say.
   Treatment of the refugees by INS has sparked a lawsuit. U.S.
District Judge Filemon Vela on Jan. 9 blocked an INS policy that had
barred asylum-seekers from traveling beyond the Rio Grande Valley
while their applications were pending. Under the INS policy, many of
the refugees had been relegated to squalid squatters' camps lacking
basic sanitation and other amenities.
   A congressional aide, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
the Justice Department hopes word of the tent-city detention center
quickly reaches Central America and discourages more amnesty-seekers
from coming to the United States.
   INS officials contend that many are seeking only to better
themselves economically and are not actually fleeing political
repression. Advocates for the refugees say many INS decisions have
been politically skewed because the U.S. government is unwilling to
admit the extent of repression by Central American governments
allied with the United States.
   The Justice Department plans to keep the refugees in tents near
the Port Isabel Service Processing Center, about 15 miles north of
Brownsville, the congressional officials said.
</TEXT>
