   Miss America Gretchen Carlson says the
public often expects beauty queens to be knowledgable on world
issues and that she wants to be remembered for addressing the
importance of family and education.
   ``There are a lot of issues that Miss America is asked to address
and people think you are an expert on every world problem,'' Miss
Carlson said during an appearance Wednesday.
   ``I would like to say that I am, but I am not,'' she said. ``So
you have to pick and choose. So those are the two that I have
decided upon.''
   Miss Carlson, 22, of Anoka, Minn., said problems related to
drugs, violence or teen-age sex are ``a manifestation of the
breakdown of the family and the discipline within our society.''
   She attributed that breakdown to homes where both parents work,
adding that much of what she has achieved was done with her family's
help.
   ``Family provides strength and guidance when you are trying to
achieve goals,'' she said.
