<FIRST>r w PM-Maritime-Defense     02-17 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Maritime-Defense,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: US Lacks Merchant Ships to Support War Effort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government should spend $13 billion over
the next decade to provide enough commercial ships for massive troop
and equipment movements should war break out, a special maritime
commission says.
   Despite that figure, the real cost to the government would be
about $5.7 billion because of the tax revenues generated by the new
ships and facilities, the Commission on Merchant Marine and Defense
said.
   The commission presented its proposals for legislative and
private action to President Bush on Thursday, but its chairman,
former GOP Sen. Jeremiah Denton, said Bush made no commitment to
seek the funds.
   The commission's proposals include a package of legislation aimed
at adding 244 ships that could be used to meet military needs. Some
of the ships would be built abroad to allow shippers to become more
quickly competitive internationally, the report said.
   Another commission member, retired Navy Adm. James L. Holloway
III, said the country probably has only 70 percent to 80 percent of
the commercial ships that might be needed in an emergency.
   ``If a crisis erupted someplace around the world, we do not have
enough ships under the American flag to support a planned
operation,'' Holloway said.
   Holloway said the maritime defense issue has not been critical in
the past because it was assumed U.S. allies could provide ships if
necessary. But he said the United States may have to ``go it
alone,'' such as it did for a time in protecting Persian Gulf
shipping.
   Troops and supplies likely would be available, he said, ``but we
don't have the sealift to move them.''
   In addition to increased ship building, the commission recommends
adding 8,208 mariners, improving ship repair yards, countering
unfair foreign trade tactics against the U.S. maritime industry and
making several reforms in laws affecting the industry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
