<DOCNO> AP890217-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-17-89 0130EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-UN-Namibia Bjt   02-17 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Namibia, Bjt,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>First U.N. Peacekeeping Official Expected In Namibia Today</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. peacekeeping forces are due in Namibia
this weekend to begin overseeing the nation's transition to
independence after 74 years of South African rule.
   Commissioner Steven Fanning, head of a U.N. police unit that will
monitor Namibia's national police force, was to arrive today in that
country, said Martti Ahtisaari, the special U.N. representative for
Namibia.
   Fanning is to hold weekend talks with Namibian police officials,
Ahtisaari said Thursday.
   Namibian police, which includes some South African officers, will
remain responsible for civil order but will be supervised by 500
U.N. police officers.
   The U.N. move into Namibia follows the Security Council's
unanimous adoption of a resolution Thursday authorizing Namibia's
independence process.
   South Africa has ruled Namibia, also known as South-West Africa,
since it captured the territory from Germany during World War I.
   Early next week, Gen. Dewan Prem Chand, the commander of the
military peacekeeping contingent, will arrive with more
administrators, said Ahtisaari.
   The Security Council set April 1 was set as the date to begin the
one-year plan for Namibia's transition to an independent, black
majority-ruled nation.
   They also approved a report by Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar that calls for sending 4,650 U.N. military peacekeepers, 500
police supervisors and at least 1,000 civilian election monitors to
Namibia.
   U.N. officials have not yet worked out which countries will
provide personnel for the peacekeeping force, but for the first time
China has offered to send up to 20 election monitors, said an Asian
diplomat.
   Perez de Cuellar has estimated the effort will cost $416 million
in its first year, making it the biggest U.N. peacekeeping mission
since the Belgian Congo operation of 1960-64, which cost more than
$400 million and involved 19,828 soldiers at its peak.
   The General Assembly on Thursday approved funds for a 70-man team
of U.N. military observers who will monitor the withdrawal of 50,000
Cuban troops from Angola as neighboring Namibia becomes independent.
   That group was budgeted at $9.2 million for this year, and a
total of $19.4 million during its entire 31-month mandate of
overseeing the Cuban withdrawal.
   In December, South Africa, Cuba and Angola signed accords at U.N.
headquarters pledging their cooperation with a southwest African
peace plan that includes the Cuban pullout and Namibian independence.
   South Africa refused to relinquish control of Namibia without the
withdrawal of the Cuban troops, saying their presence just over
Namibia's northern border could intimidate voters during the
independence process.
   All Cuban troops are to be out of Angola by July 1991.
   Cuban troops have been in Angola at that country's request since
1975 to defend it from attacks by South African troops and the
U.S.-backed rebels of the National Union for the Total Liberation of
Angola.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
