<FIRST>r w PM-DrugReport     02-17 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug Report,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Urges International Cooperation in Drug Fight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House narcotics committee's report on drug
use says the problem will become even graver without greater
international cooperation.
   Citing an increase in cocaine-related deaths last year, the
report said, ``With the continued influx of cocaine into this
country, the prospects for any change in this situation in the near
future are not promising.''
   The report by the House Select Committee on Narcotics Abuse and
Control added that current estimates of the scope of drug abuse may
understate the problem.
   ``Without a concerted international commitment, including a
hemispheric drug summit, and without increased resources at home,
the future picture is bleak,'' Chairman Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., said
Thursday.
   The report said indicators showed an increase last year in coca
and cocaine production and trafficking as well as greater opium and
marijuana cultivation, despite reports of stepped up eradication
efforts in some countries.
   The report catalogued a substantial haul of narcotics intercepted
by federal agencies on their way into the United States but noted
official estimates that the amount intercepted represents no more
than 5 percent to 15 percent of what comes across the border.
   ``Despite the best efforts ... drugs continue to flood our
borders because of bumper crops in producing countries,'' the report
said. It said that ``the influx of drugs places a significant burden
on federal, state and local law enforcement efforts.''
   The panel also estimated that 6 million to 6.5 million Americans
need drug abuse treatment and said there are 1.1 million to 1.3
million intravenous drug abusers.
   Currently, however, there are only about 250,000 treatment slots,
according to the committee. It said about 148,000 are for
intravenous abusers.
   ``Long waiting lists are common in many areas,'' it said.
``Moreover, there is no measure of those who are discouraged from
even applying.''
   The panel said hospital emergency rooms recorded 1,696
cocaine-related deaths last year, up from 604 such cases in 1984.
</TEXT>
