<FIRST>r a PM-AirbrushedFirefighter     02-17 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Airbrushed Firefighter,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Can Sue Union for Emotional Distress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black firefighter who was airbrushed out
of a photograph in a union's newsletter can sue the group for
emotional distress, a Superior Court judge has ruled.
   The omission of Charles Johnson from the August 1987 photo did
not amount to a statement that was libelous or portrayed him in a
false light, said Judge Stuart Pollak, dismissing those two counts
of Johnson's suit.
   But in the ruling Wednesday, Pollak said Johnson could sue
Firefighters Local 798 and two members involved in the newsletter
for intentional infliction of emotional distress, which requires
proof of ``outrageous'' conduct.
   Johnson was one of several San Francisco firefighters honored for
a rescue effort. The photograph in the union's newsletter, Mainline,
was altered to remove Johnson, the only black and only non-union
member in the group. Johnson belongs to the Black Firefighters
Association, a separate organization.
   In his suit, he said the omission caused him humiliation and
stress that kept him off the job.
   The incident happened within a few months of the discovery of a
swastika in an office used by two minority firefighters, and the
manhandling by whites of an officer involved in a department
training program for women and minorities.
   Those episodes were cited by a federal judge who pronounced the
Fire Department ``out of control'' in January 1988. Shortly
afterward, Chief Edward Phipps resigned and was succeeded by
Frederick Postel.
   The union apologized to Johnson over the photograph but said he
was omitted only because he was not a member of the union, which has
some minority members.
   ``I have a hard time accepting the idea that a union or any other
organization has a duty to publish pictures of non-members,'' said
Duane Reno, a lawyer for Local 798. ``Even if the person does feel
left out, there should be a privilege that says the organization is
free to grant publicity to its members.''
   He said the union would make another attempt to dismiss the
emotional distress claim before trial.
   Howard Moore, Johnson's lawyer, said the suit would be redrafted
to try to reinstate the libel and ``false light'' claims.
</TEXT>
