<FIRST>r i PM-Sweden-Submarines     02-17 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sweden-Submarines,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Sub Intrusions Continue Off Sweden</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign submarines probed waters off
Sweden last year as often as before, but appeared to back off after
Swedish forces fired at a suspected intruder, the military said in
its annual report.
   The eight-page report that was released Thursday said, ``In spite
of a number of observations, technical indications and
well-coordinated action by anti-submarine warfare units, we have no
evidence of the nationality involved.''
   But the Svenska Dagbladet daily newspaper said the Soviet Union
was singled out in a secret appendix to the report submitted to
Prime Minister Ingvar Carlsson's government.
   The Soviets have denied sending submarines into Swedish territory
since 1981 when a vessel washed onto the rocks outside a major
Swedish naval base. Moscow called that incident a mistake.
   Supreme Commander Gen. Bengt Gustafsson told reporters the
military had some ideas about the identity of the intruders, but not
enough to warrant diplomatic action.
   Naval commander Vice Admiral Bengt Schuback told a military
seminar last month there was little doubt the intruders were Soviet
vessels.
   ``They can't come from anywhere but hidden bases in the Baltic,
and we know Western countries have no such bases,'' he said.
   Gustafsson said there had been a drop in the number of intrusions
since late last year when ``the one who is violating our territorial
waters began to act more carefully'' after the government fired on
the suspected intruding sub last June off the coast.
   Gustafsson said the live-fire response followed
government-aprroved guidelines established in 1987 to prevent
intruders from escaping.
</TEXT>
