<FIRST>r w PM-Banks-Redlining     02-17 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Banks-Redlining,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Activists See Strengthened Enforcement of Discrimination Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Community activists say they are heartened by
the Federal Reserve Board's decision to strengthen enforcement of a
12-year-old law forbidding loan discrimination against neighborhoods.
   The reaction Thursday followed the Fed's rejection of a request
by the Chicago-based Continental Bank Corp., the nation's 11th
largest, to purchase a small Arizona bank. It cited Continental's
lackluster record of serving poor neighborhoods as required by the
Community Reinvestment Act.
   The law, passed in 1977, is aimed at preventing ``redlining,''
the practice of denying loans to an entire neighborhood based on the
predominant race or economic class of its residents.
   Although the Fed had previously granted merger requests on the
condition that the banks applying did a better job of community
reinvestment in the future, it had never denied an application.
   ``We hope this is the beginning of a trend,'' said Allen
Fishbein, general counsel of the Center for Community Change, a
Washington-based group concerned with housing and community
development. ``For a board composed entirely of Reagan
administration appointees, this is an unprecedented step.''
   Diane Casey, director of regulatory affairs for the Independent
Bankers Association of America, said the Fed appears to be trying to
head off action in Congress, which last year considered several
measures requiring regulators to more vigorously enforce
anti-redlining laws.
   ``I think the Fed is letting Congress know that the existing law
is more than strong enough for the Fed to take action ... and that
means you don't have to go through a significant restructuring'' of
the act, she said.
   However, Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas and chairman of the
House Banking Committee, said members of his panel were still very
interested in toughening the law.
   ``The interest here is still ... intense,'' he said. ``The Fed's
isolated and late awakening has to be viewed in the light of its
prior compliance or lack of compliance.''
   Continental's 14-month-old petition to acquire Grand Canyon State
Bank in Scottsdale, Ariz., was rejected on a 4-2 vote Wednesday,
with board members H. Robert Heller and John LaWare opposed. Edward
W. Kelley Jr. did not vote.
   ``We feel that the Fed has finally put teeth into the law,'' said
Michael Zucker, an international representative of the Amalgamated
Clothing and Textile Workers Union, which had lodged a formal
complaint against Continental's application.
   Zucker said Continental ``never has done a good job of lending to
the low-income and minority community of Chicago.'' He described
Grand Canyon as a ``boutique bank'' catering to affluent customers
in suburban Phoenix.
   However, Thomas C. Theobald, the chairman of Continental, said he
was ``astounded and outraged'' at the Fed's decision. ``We have an
excellent and always improving record of community support,'' he
said.
   The central bank's 10-page majority decision said, ``Given
Continental's size ... (the) bank's participation in community
development and redevelopment efforts was unsatisfactory.''
   It noted the bank has since developed a plan that should ``make
substantial contribution to correcting the past deficiencies,'' but
added, ``The board does not believe that commitments by themselves
can serve as a substitute for the established record of ...
performance.''
   The Fed also voiced concern about the bank's plan to expand while
still financed in part by and subject to the control of Federal
Deposit Insurance Corp., as the result of a 1984 federal rescue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
