<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--SchoolSecurity     02-17 0151</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--School Security,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Affluent County to Use Drug-Sniffing Dogs, Metal Detectors in Schools</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRFAX, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the most affluent counties in the
nation is turning to drug-sniffing dogs and metal detectors in an
attempt to stem the flow of drugs and weapons into its high schools.
   ``These are precautionary measures in the system to make sure the
parents and community feel comfortable,'' Fairfax County
Superintendent Robert Spillane said Thursday.
   The action comes after several recent incidents involving weapons
at Washington, D.C.-area schools. An affluent suburb of the nation's
capital, Fairfax County is the largest school district in the
Washington area.
   Metal detectors will be used when administrators have
``reasonable cause'' to believe a student has a weapon, said Deputy
Superintendent Doris Torice.
   Principals will decide when and how often to use drug-sniffing
dogs. Entire halls or buildings will be inspected, not just
individual students, officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
