<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     02-17 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to restore cycle designator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Efforts by California's Hollywood to get a
trademark on the name have commissioners in this south Florida city
seeing stars.
   ``We don't believe we should have to get their permission to use
our own city's name,'' Mayor Mara Giulianti said. ``We are a duly
incorporated city, and they aren't even a city.''
   If the movie capital on the Pacific Coast gets the trademark, all
other Hollywoods would have to pay to use the city name. An
exception would be made for the area within the city limits of
Hollywood, Fla.
   But City Manager Irv Rosenbaum says that's not good enough.
   ``We market tourism nationally,'' he said. ``We're the
eighth-largest city in the state. We should be able to use our name
wherever.''
   At least seven other Hollywoods _ in Alabama, Louisiana,
Maryland, Missouri, New Mexico, South Carolina and West Virginia _
would face the same problem, Giulianti said.
   The Chamber of Commerce of Hollywood, Calif., actually a district
of Los Angeles, filed for the trademark on its name Jan. 17.
   The Florida city had only until Feb. 17 to file its objection,
but has asked for a 30-day extension from the U.S. Trademarks Office.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: A version moved on sports wires on Feb. 15.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The winner and still heavyweight champion of
the world after the legendary ``long count'' is ... Gene Tunney.
   There were no knockdowns in the courtroom, but Tunney won a clear
verdict over Jack Dempsey from a historical judge on Wednesday. The
unofficial ruling somewhat vindicated a controversial decision by a
referee 62 years ago.
   In front of chuckling onlookers at ``ringside'' at the mock Court
of Historical Review and Appeals, Municipal Judge George T.
Choppelas declared the long-count controversy ``null and void.''
   ``Gene Tunney deserves full credit for the victory,'' the judge
said.
   Almost all the evidence was in Tunney's corner. Tunney's son,
former Sen. John V. Tunney, said the long count, in which his father
lay on the canvas for nine of the slowest counts in the history of
boxing, was ``the luckiest thing that ever happened'' to either
fighter.
   ``It kept their names in the public forum and gave added luster
to both their careers,'' Tunney said.
   If the controversy over the famous 1927 title fight was heated,
Wednesday's session was not. But that's not unusual for the Court of
Historical Review.
   The just-for-fun court, which convenes over lunch, has previously
settled such weighty issues as the origin of the martini (Martinez,
Calif.) and whether Santa Claus is real (You bet).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
