<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     02-17 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shares Hit Record High, Dollar Edges Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices reversed an earlier trend to close the
week at a record high Friday, while the U.S. dollar edged lower as
dealers waited in anticipation of an American trade report scheduled
for release later in the day.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 65.90-point
loser the previous day, won back 89.81 points, or 0.28 percent, for
32,173.39 by the end of the trading week.
   In foreign exchange dealings, the dollar closed at 125.72 yen,
down 0.61 yen from Thursday's 126.33-yen finish. It traded in a
tight range of 125.50-125.90 yen during the day.
   Dealers said the market's main economic barometer suffered a late
morning slump when it shed a minor 1.36 points after jumping over
100 points shortly after the exchange opened. The index again picked
up steam in the afternoon session before finishing the week at yet
another high.
   The previous record was set Wednesday when the Nikkei closed at
32,149.48.
   Dealers said market participants were refraining from making
strong moves ahead of American trade figures scheduled for release
by the U.S Commerce Department later Friday, Tokyo time.
   They expect the December trade deficit to total $11 billion to
$12 billion, slightly lower from November's $12.5 billion, the
dealers added.
   ``The dollar is a lot weaker than I thought,'' said a dealer with
a major securities firm. ``It came under selling pressure once it
broke the 128.00-yen level,'' he added, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   ``If the trade deficit is over $12 billion, the U.S. currency is
likely to weaken even more.''
</TEXT>
