<FILEID>AP-NR-02-17-89 0302EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     02-17 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Off Slightly, Stocks Hit Record High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tokyo dealers took to the sidelines today as the
U.S. dollar shed ground against the Japanese yen, while active
buying propelled the market's main economic barometer to another
record closing.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues started with more
than a 100-point surge at the onset of trading, but fizzled out
toward the end of the morning after profit-taking by investors. By
the end of the early session, the index, a 65.90-point loser
Thursday, had shed a marginal 1.36 points.
   Led by active buying of large-capital issues, the Nikkei regained
momentum in the afternoon session and managed to win back 89.91
points, or 0.28 percent, during the two hours of trading. It closed
the week at 32,173.39 points, a record finish.
   The previous high was set Wednesday when the index finished at
32,149.48 points.
   In foreign exchange dealings, the dollar closed at 125.72 yen,
down 0.61 yen from Thursday's 126.33-yen finish. It was traded in a
tight range of 125.50-125.90 yen during the day.
   The U.S. currency had opened at a lower 125.90 yen following
losses in overseas markets, and one dealer said the dollar came
under strong selling pressure after it broke the 125.80-yen level,
which he described as ``a technical point.''
   Speaking on condition of anonymity, the dealer added that
movement of the dollar against the yen next week will depend on what
the American trade deficit figure for December totals.
   The U.S. Commerce Department is scheduled to release the figure
in Washington later today and many local economists have predicted
it to be slightly lower than November's $12.5 billion.
   But ``if the trade deficit is over $12 billion, the U.S. currency
is likely to weaken even more,'' the dealer said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
