<DOCNO> AP890217-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-17-89 0456EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Morocco-Summit     02-17 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Morocco-Summit,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>North African Leaders Open Summit To Create New Union</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Arabs-Unity Pacts, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARRAKECH, Morocco (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of Moroccans welcomed
the leaders of five North African nations who are holding a summit
to create a common market known as the Great Magreb.
   ``This union is only the first stage toward a union of all Arab
countries,'' Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi told leaders of Algeria,
Mauritania, Morocco and Tunisia at the opening session Thursday.
   They proposed to finalize their treaty today following prayers in
Marrakech's nearly 1,000-year-old Kotoubia Mosque.
   The outlines of the future union remain general, but summit
sources said the leaders want the new union to enable their
countries to hold their own in dealing with the European Economic
Community.
   King Hassan II on Thursday said the nations are realizing ``a
dream that North Africans have had for generations.''
   Outside the meeting in Marrakech City Hall, more than 20,000
people cheered the leaders.
   Col. Gadhafi announced that a second summit conference of what is
being called the ``Arab Union of the Great Maghreb'' would take
place in Libya's capital, Tripoli, on Sept. 1. The day is also the
20th anniversary of the coup that brought him to power.
   Gadhafi also hoped that someday ``other African countries,
particularly Sudan, Chad, Mali and Niger'' would join the union.
   Gadhafi has proposed integrating the defense forces of the five
countries, but none of the other four summit nations has shown an
interest in the move.
   Within the union, all goods would move freely, and there would be
separate agreements on the free movement of their citizens,
unification of currencies, and economic relations with the outside
world.
   But each country would retain its national sovereignty.
   In Baghdad, Iraq, the leaders of Egypt, Iraq, Jordan and North
Yemen signed an accord Thursday also to create an economic alliance,
an official Iraqi report said.
   Their alliance, called the Arab Cooperation Council, is designed
to boost Arab unity, the Iraqi News Agency said.
</TEXT>
