<DOCNO> AP890217-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-17-89 0535EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Paraguay     02-17 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Paraguay,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Acknowledges Stroessner's Police Had Torture Chambers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new interior minister acknowledged
that police under ousted President Alfredo Strossner had torture
chambers, but he said they would be dismantled soon, a newspaper
reported.
   The comments by Gen. Orlando Machuca Vargas followed accusations
in recent years by Paraguay's Roman Catholic Church and human rights
organizations that Gen. Stroessner used torture to repress political
opposition.
   In an interview with the newspaper El Diario Noticias, Machuca
Vargas was quoted as saying his ministry would crack down on rights
violations by police.
   ``We are going to eliminate torture chambers in police stations
since they do nothing for the image of the country and are degrading
to the human condition,'' he was quoted as saying.
   The interior minister declined to give details of the ``torture
chambers'' but said they will be shut down, probably ``within a
month.''
   Stroessner was deposed Feb. 3 in a coup by Gen. Andres Rodriguez,
who named himself provisional president, appointed a new Cabinet,
and accepted the governing Colorado Party's endorsement for
president in elections set for May 1. About 50 people were killed in
the coup, the government said.
   Human rights groups said Stroessner's forces frequently used
torture.
   After he consolidated power following a 1954 coup, Stroessner
eased up on the most blatant human rights violations, replacing
murder and torture with harassment, detentions and expulsions, the
rights groups charged.
   Machuca Vargas said members of the investigative police agency,
which long has been accused of torturing political and criminal
prisoners, will be prosecuted if formal complaints are lodged.
   ``We will investigate all the irregularities committed by
employees of this ministry,'' he was quoted as saying. ``We're not
going to cover up for anybody. ... Our mission is to clean up the
image of the Interior Ministry as being a repressive organ of the
government.''
   In a separate development, a judge ordered the release of a
Chilean convicted of being an accomplice in the September 1980
assassination of exiled Nicaraguan president Anastasio Somoza.
   Rafael Mella Latorre was arrested in October 1980, 47 days after
Somoza's car was blasted by a bazooka in a residential neighborhood
of this capital city.
   ``I'm emphatic in saying I had no participation in that. I was a
scapegoat of authorities in charge of the custody of Somoza,'' Mella
Latorre told reporters.
   ``The investigative police tortured me for almost seven months.
They even tortured my pregnant wife in my presence, causing a
miscarriage,'' he said.
   Mella Latorre was scheduled to be released in 1986 after being
convicted and sentenced to six years in prison, but prison officials
accused him of participating in a prison riot that January. Judge
Tito Medina decreed his release after a witness testified Mella
Latorre was not involved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
