<DOCNO> AP890217-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-17-89 0537EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Pakistan-Book     02-17 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pakistan-Book,0577</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bhutto May Face Problems Over `Satanic Verses' Furor</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Satanic Verses, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opponents of Prime Minister Benezir
Bhutto may be trying to undermine her goverment by using the rage of
a novel that allegedly blasphemes Islam.
   The furor over ``The Satanic Verses'' caused the most violent
demonstration in the Pakistani capital in a decade and occurred
while Ms. Bhutto was in China on her first official trip abroad as
prime minister.
   ``If the real purpose of the demonstration was only to protest
the book, it came at an odd time and an odd place,'' said a retired
bureaucrat who served under both Ms. Bhutto's father, the late Prime
Minister Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, and President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq, who
overthrew Bhutto in 1977.
   On Sunday, young Moslems following religious leaders and
political opponents of Ms. Bhutto's Pakistan People's Party marched
on the U.S. Information Center in Islamabad to demand that the
United States, a close ally of Pakistan, ban the book.
   A rock-throwing mob smashed windows, tore down the American flag
and started small fires in the building.
   Police responded with tear gas and gunfire. Six people were shot
to death and more than 80 were injured.
   Ms. Bhutto said the violence appeared to be the work of her
political rivals and accused them of trying to whip up sentiment
against the 2-month-old government.
   Pakistan already had joined Iran, India, Bangladesh, Egypt and
South Africa in banning the novel.
   An editorial in The Frontier Post, an English-language newspaper
that often supports the Bhutto party, declared: ``The path of
confrontation ... is being followed by people who either do not
accept the democratic way of life or are not happy with the results
of the general elections and now wish to destabilize the popularly
elected government.''
   Organizers of the protest said the timing had nothing to do with
Ms. Bhutto's absence in China, but was prompted by reviews of the
book that appeared in international news magazines a few days
earlier.
   A government official said privately: ``The reviews had the first
details anyone had about the book. Nobody here has read the book.''
   A religious issue could bring together followers of Zia, who won
the support of Moslem fundamentalist parties by espousing Islamic
law for Pakistan. The program had made little headway by the time
Zia was killed in a plane crash in August.
   Zia's political heirs ran in November's elections as the
eight-party Islamic Democratic Alliance, with adoption of Islamic
law as a major part of their platform. Ms. Bhutto has shunned
Islamization as a relic of the Zia years.
   Her party, founded by her father, won the popular vote nearly 2-1
in Pakistan's first free elections since the 1977 coup. It fell
short of a majority in Parliament, however, and she formed a
coalition with small parties and independents.
   Ms. Bhutto's lack of a majority has led to several confrontations
with the conservatives, the most notable over her attempt to repeal
a constitutional amendment Zia enacted giving the president broad
discretionary powers.
   Moslems say ``The Satanic Verses'' offends their faith by
satirizing the prophet Mohammed as fallible and implying that Islam
is not the only true religion.
   Author Salman Rushdie, a British citizen who was born in India to
Moslem parents, says the work is not blasphemous.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890217-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-17-89 0545EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Burma-Fire     02-17 0121</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burma-Fire,0126</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Destroys 3,900 Buildings, Leaves 23,000 Homeless</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire in the southeastern city of Mergui
destroyed 3,900 buildings and left 22,000 residents homeless,
official sources said today.
   There was no report on casualties or the cause of Thursday's
inferno, which sources said caused an estimated $50 million damage.
   Among the structures destroyed were two schools, three movie
theaters, a section of a hospital and a government office building.
   The blaze broke out at 3 p.m. and lasted until midnight.
   Mergui, 350 miles southeast of Rangoon, is a prosperous business
center with a wealthy Chinese-Burmese community.
   Several large fires have swept through Burma's provincial centers
in recent years, in part because many buildings are wooden.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890217-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-17-89 0549EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Egypt-Book     02-17 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Egypt-Book,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Theologian Says Khomeini Mistaken To Order Author's Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Satanic Verses, Bjt ^By NEJLA SAMMAKIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ayatollah Khomeini has made a religious
mistake in sending death squads after the author of ``The Satanic
Verses,'' a leading Islamic theologian said.
   Executing Salman Rushdie would be ``virtually impossible'' under
the tenets of Islam and such a death order is ``a wrong ruling''
from a theological point of view, said Sheik Mohammed Hossam-el-Din
of Cairo's Al-Azhar institute.
   Hossam-el-Din said Thursday that the book should be banned and
burned, but that nobody has been executed in Islam's 1,350-year
history as an apostate, which he interpreted as the crime Khomeini
invoked in his death sentence.
   Khomeini said the Indian-born author deserved to die for
insulting Islam.
   Rushdie, born into a wealthy Moslem family in Bombay, says he
does not believe in ``supernatural entities'' but insists his book
is not slanderous.
   The 1,013-year-old Al-Azhar is considered the Moslem world's
center of theology, combining a university and mosque whose
officials are appointed by the government.
   Khomeini's execution order and unrest in Pakistan, India and Iran
over the book's publication make ``Islam seem brutal and
bloodthirsty,'' said Hossam-el-Din.
   He said there are four steps to follow with someone suspected of
being an apostate before passing a death sentence:
   _ A formal court questions the defendant on his motivation and
whether his alleged offense was meant to signify rejection of Islam.
   _ Once held to be an apostate, the defendant is given a week to
repent.
   _ Barring repentance, he is sentenced to death. The only
authority enabled to pass such a sentence, however, is a Moslem
ruler with jurisdiction over the defendant.
   _ Finally, if the defendant changes his mind and eventually
repents at any time before his execution _ even the second before
death _ he is absolved and released.
   ``So you see, it's really impossible to execute an apostate
because the defendant will always repent,'' Hossam-el-Din said.
   ``Whoever understands Islam will realize that the penalty for
apostacy cannot be implemented. In the history of Islam, there has
never been any individual case of executing an apostate, only wars
against them.''
   He said he has not read the book but that Al-Azhar officials have
received reports and excerpts from Moslem clerics in London.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
