<DOCNO> AP890217-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-17-89 0617EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-SAfrica-WhiteNation 1stLd-Writethru a0486 02-17 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-White Nation, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0486,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Right-Wing Group Details Plans For Whites-Only Nation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2 grafs for grafs 5-6 pvs, ``Boshoff is ...'' to CORRECT
spelling of Verwoerd sted Verweord. Pickup 7th graf pvs, ``Boshoff contends
...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of right-wing academics
who believe black majority rule is inevitable have proposed creating
an all-white, Afrikaner nation in a thinly populated section of
western South Africa.
   Carel Boshoff, leader of the Afrikaner Freedom Movement, outlined
details of the proposed nation Thursday that he said would include
the Atlantic coastline starting about 60 miles north of Cape Town
and extend 300 miles inland. The area contains no major cities, and
much of it is desert.
   Boshoff's as-yet-nameless nation also would include the southern
half of Namibia, but that South African-ruled territory is due to
gain independence by early next year.
   His proposal contrasts sharply with the demand of a nationwide
extremist group, the Afrikaner Resistance Movement, for creation of
a whites-only state consisting of Transvaal and the Orange Free
State, two of South Africa's four provinces. Both provinces have
vast farming areas and numerous gold mines, and Transvaal includes
the major cities of Pretoria and Johannesburg.
   Boshoff is a theologian and a former chairman of the Broederbond,
a secretive society of influential Afrikaners. He is the son-in-law
of the late Prime Minister Hendrik Verwoerd, who designed South
Africa's apartheid system in the 1950s.
   Boshoff's proposal represents a reversal of the ideology of
Verwoerd, who sought to relocate blacks in nominally independent
rural homelands while whites controlled the bulk of the country,
including the industrial centers, gold mines, ports and best
farmland.
   Boshoff contends establishment of a small, whites-only nation is
the only way of ensuring the survival of the Afrikaners, the mainly
Dutch-descended whites who make up about 60 percent of South
Africa's 5 million whites.
   In a controversial policy document last year, Boshoff said
Afrikaners should abandon hope of dominating the entire country,
where the 26 million blacks outnumber whites more than 5-to-1.
   ``Minority domination as currently practiced in South Africa is
morally unjustifiable,'' he wrote.
   The National Party government rejects the idea of a white
homeland. It is struggling to find support for its concept of racial
power-sharing, in which blacks would be brought into central
government but would not be allowed to overrule white interests.
   Boshoff said he envisioned a transitional period in which
Afrikaners would move to the proposed white nation while it remained
under South African control. He said infrastructure would be
improved with government grants similar to those extended to black
homelands.
   Boshoff acknowledged the area is dry, but suggested that the
region along the Orange River, which forms the South Africa-Namibia
border, could be developed for agriculture.
   ``A move to the area would change the lifestyle of people as they
know it now, but they have a choice of staying in the fat of South
Africa and melting away or move toward a new beginning,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
