<FILEID>AP-NR-02-17-89 0633EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AtlantaMayoral     02-17 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Atlanta Mayoral,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>It's Maynard For Mayor, Despite Possible Pay Cut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maynard Jackson, the first black man to serve as
mayor of Atlanta, has announced his candidacy for another term in
the office he left in 1981, although he concedes that victory could
be costly.
   ``We're about to take one big reduction in income,'' Jackson said
Thursday as he announced his candidacy with his wife, Valerie, from
the steps of City Hall.
   Jackson, a Democrat, has been working as a partner in a
Chicago-based law firm since he left office. Financially, he said,
running for mayor is ``the single most irrational move of my life.''
   Right now, Jackson's only opponent is Fulton County Commissioner
Michael Lomax, who has said he wouldn't keep all of the $100,000
salary approved by the Atlanta City Council earlier this month.
Mayor Andrew Young currently earns $65,000 per year.
   Young was elected mayor in 1981 when Jackson was barred by the
city charter from seeking a third consecutive term. Young is
required to leave office under the same charter provision.
   Jackson was first elected mayor in October 1973, defeating
incumbent Sam Massell with 60 percent of the vote.
   In a brief campaign speech, Jackson said he committed himself to
public service in 1968 because he wanted a ``more prosperous Atlanta
for all Atlantans.'' He identified the issues of his latest campaign
as drugs, crime and assistance for elderly citizens.
   ``I have listened carefully over the years ... and people are
asking for help,'' Jackson said. ``That's why I'm running for mayor
of Atlanta. I promise you help is on the way.''
</TEXT>
