<FIRST>r a PM-Giuliani     02-17 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Giuliani,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Giuliani, Still Considering Mayoral Race, Joins Law Firm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former U.S. Attorney Rudolph W. Giuliani has
joined a prominent law firm but kept open a possible mayoral
candidacy, saying he is carefully considering running and is
encouraged by the support he has found.
   In joining the Manhattan-based law firm of White &amp; Case, Giuliani
said Thursday, ``I told them, assume I'm running for mayor and let's
structure the relationship out of that, so there'd be no
misunderstanding.''
   Still, he insisted at a luncheon with reporters that he was
undecided about entering the race and viewed it as his
responsibility to move with care. He said he was holding discussions
to gauge if he had sufficient support.
   ``I'm continuing to explore the possibility of running for
mayor,'' he said, adding that it was prudence, not indecision, that
has led to his long courtship with the prospect.
   Giuliani, a Republican, would face Ronald S. Lauder, former
ambassador to Austria and heir to the Lauder cosmetics fortune, in
his party's primary.
   If he ran, Giuliani said, he would accept the city's voluntary
spending limit of $3 million each for the primary and general
election. Lauder has said he would not accept that limit and the
public financing that comes with it.
   Giuliani would have the power of his public profile as a
successful prosecutor to counter Lauder's cash advantage. The winner
would face the Democratic nominee in this heavily Democratic city,
where a Republican has not won for mayor since John Lindsay in 1965.
</TEXT>
