<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     02-17 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain From Texas to North Carolina, Snow From Northwest to Mississippi
Valley</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain fell from Texas to North Carolina today, prompting a flash
flood watch in the Lone Star State, as snow fell from the Pacific
Northwest to the upper Mississippi Valley.
   The rain was heaviest from west-central to northeast Texas, where
showers and a few thunderstorms left up to 3 inches of
precipitation. A flash flood watch was issued for the extreme
southwest section of the state.
   Freezing rain fell in southwest Oklahoma, and scattered showers
fell from southern Oklahoma to Arkansas and North Carolina. The
northern Pacific Coast also had rain.
   Snow extended from inland Oregon and Washington to the northern
Rockies, the northern Plains and the upper Mississippi Valley. By
late Thursday, up to 6 inches of snow had fallen in Minnesota and
the Continental Divide in Montana, and up to 4 inches in South
Dakota. Spokane, Wash., got 5 inches.
   A winter storm warning was in effect for the northwest mountains
of Montana and passes west of the Continental Divide. Up to 8 inches
of snow was expected with winds up to 35 mph and wind chills down to
50 below.
   Winter storm warnings were also issued for northeast Washington
and valleys near the Cascade Mountains in the south central section
of the state.
   Today's forecast called for rain along the Pacific Northwest
coast and from Texas to the lower Mississippi and Tennessee valleys,
northern sections of the Gulf Coast states and most of the
Carolinas; snow from higher elevations of Oregon and Washington to
the northern and central Rockies, parts of the northern and central
Great Plains and the upper Mississippi Valley; snow mixed with sleet
and freezing rain from northwest Texas to Oklahoma, southeast
Kansas, central Missouri, the Ohio Valley, much of West Virginia,
southwest Virginia and northern North Carolina; and sunshine
prevailing in the Southwest, New England and Florida.
   High temperatures were forecast from 10 below to 10 above zero in
the northern Plains; in the teens and 20s from northern Idaho to
Wyoming, parts of the central Plains, the upper Mississippi Valley,
the Great Lakes and much of northern New England; the 50s and 60s in
most of California, Arizona and New Mexico, with readings in the 70s
in southern Arizona; the 50s and 60s from southern Texas to the Gulf
Coast and South Carolina; the 70s to mid-80s in Florida; and the 30s
and 40s elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 22
degrees below zero at Warroad, Minn., to 74 degrees at Homestead,
Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 54 windy; Boston 15 partly cloudy; Buffalo 12
fair; Charleston, S.C. 48 drizzle; Cincinnati 28 cloudy; Cleveland
18 partly cloudy; Detroit 18 fair; Miami 72 partly cloudy; New York
22 partly cloudy; Philadelphia 25 partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 19
cloudy; Washington 34 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck -5 snow; Chicago 19 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 44
rain; Denver 21 hazy; Des Moines 13 cloudy; Indianapolis 27 cloudy;
