<FIRST>u i PM-Germany-SatanicVerses     02-17 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Satanic Verses,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iranian Ambassador Warned On Rushdie Threat, Top Diplomat Recalled</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Satanic Verses, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The West German government today
expressed deep consternation over Iran's death threats against
author Salman Rushdie and ordered its top diplomat back to Bonn.
   In Cologne, the owner of the German-language rights to ``The
Satanic Verses'' said today it would not publish the controversial
book out of concern for the safety of the company's employees.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Juergen Chrobog said the Iranian
ambassador to West Germany, Mehdi Ahary Mostafavi, was summoned to
the Foreign Ministry today and warned that the death threat poses
``an encumbrance for German-Iranian relations.''
   West Germany is Iran's biggest trading partner and has more than
100 businesses with representatives in the Islamic republic.
   The Bonn government's warning was delivered to the Iranian envoy
by foreign affairs secretary Juergen Sudhoff at the instruction of
Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher, Chrobog told reporters at a
press conference.
   ``The deep consternation of the federal government over the death
threat against Salman Rushdie was conveyed,'' Chrobog said.
   Genscher has also ordered the charge d'affairs in Tehran to
return to Bonn, the Foreign Ministry reported.
   Foreign Ministers of the European Community plan to meet in
Brussels on Monday to discuss the execution order issued by
Ayatollah Khomeini against the Indian-born British author of ``The
Satanic Verses.''
   The book has set off a furor in the much of the Moslem world, and
Iran has offered a bounty of up to $5.2 million for the murder of
Rushdie.
   Many Moslems claim that the book's portrayal of the prophet
Mohammed, founder of the Islamic faith, as a philandering
businessman is blasphemous.
   In a statement distributed to the news media, the prestigious
Kiepenheuer und Witsch publishing company today explained its
reasons for refusing to publish the book.
   ``We have decided not to publish the novel `The Satanic Verses,'
in order to not endanger the life and limb of the employees in the
current situation,'' the statement said.
   The publishing firm owns the German-language rights to the book,
and the decision means that Rushdie's work will not be available to
readers in West Germany, Switzerland and Austria in their own
language.

</TEXT>
