<SECOND>PM-Kidnap Murder,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Accused Killer Arrives In New Jersey To Face Prosecution; Teen Victim
Mourned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MORAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of stabbing a teen-ager to
death and taking another captive on a cross-country flight from
justice was returned to New Jersey today to face prosecution.
   Michael Ardila, 19, was scheduled to be arraigned on murder and
kidnapping charges in the death of Anthony Pompelio, 17, of Sparta,
who was killed Sunday after he tried to break up an argument between
Ardila and Donna Shaban, 17.
   Police said Ardila then abducted Shaban, also of Sparta, and fled
in a stolen car.
   Shaban was found Tuesday near Groom, Texas, and told police
Ardila had pushed her from the car as they drove along the highway.
   Ardila was captured Tuesday near Santa Rosa, N.M. Authorities
said he crashed through a police roadblock and overturned his
vehicle amid a hail of gunfire from sheriff's deputies.
   On Thursday, Pompelio was eulogized as a hero for trying to
defend Shaban.
   ``He was a faithful young man who died defending another,'' said
Monsignor Francis J. Bischoff. ``He would never hurt anyone. He was
just in the wrong place at the wrong time.''
   About 500 classmates and family members gathered for Pompelio's
funeral at St. Michael's Church in Netcong. The students were
excused from classes at Sparta High School and Pompelio's wrestling
teammates served as pall bearers.
   Shaban returned to New Jersey early Wednesday accompanied by her
mother.
</TEXT>
