<FIRST>r a PM-HomelessDeath     02-17 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Homeless Death,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homeless Man Dies With $2,000 In Pocket</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A homeless man who read erudite publications by
street lights and reportedly never asked for handouts was found dead
on an Upper East Side street, carrying $2,000 in his pocket.
   ``We all figured he wasn't broke, he was just a broken man,''
said Donald DaVanzo, an electrician at a construction site near
where Richard DeMattia, 46, was found dead early Thursday.
   DeMattia had lived on East 66th Street in Manhattan for at least
a year, storing his belongings inside a church, while his mother,
Lucille DeMattia, who lives about 10 miles away in Queens, tried
desperately to find him.
   Mrs. DeMattia told a local newspaper she had hired a private
detective at one point to try to track down her son, whom she said
was a veteran receiving disability payments.
   She said she did not know he had been homeless until late
Thursday, when police traced her through an identification card her
son was carrying.
   When asked how she and her son, whom she hadn't seen since 1986,
became estranged, she said, ``It's a long story.''
   DeMattia had a bank account with $638 dollars in it at the time
of his death, which apparently was due to natural causes, said
Manhattan Chief of Detectives Aaron Rosenthal.
   ``He also had $2,000 cash on his person,'' Rosenthal said, adding
that his source of income was unclear.
   He was known to area residents and merchants as ``Charlie'' and
``Philip,'' and stayed mostly on East 66th Street between York and
First avenues.
   ``He was a peaceful man. No one ever felt threatened by him,''
said Connie Adamec, a resident of the block.
   The Rev. Robert Tomlian, pastor of the St. John Nepomucene Roman
Catholic Church, said DeMattia kept his belongings near a
confessional and spent much of his time during the day inside the
church. Only on extremely cold nights would he sleep in the church
basement.
   Ms. Adamec said that she and other neighbors tried repeatedly to
get Damattia to go to a homeless shelter, but he always said he
preferred life on the street.
   Tabassam Qureshi, who owns two newsstands on First Avenue near
66th Street, said DeMattia was a regular customer who bought The
Christian Science Monitor and The Wall Street Journal.
   ``I don't know, maybe he had a share in something,'' Qureshi said.
   DaVanzo said he sometimes saw DeMattia, who said he was an
electronics engineer, read The Nation or Scientific American as he
lay beneath his quilts.
   ``His shoes were always shined,'' he said. ``I guess there was
something in his life he couldn't deal with _ and it broke him.''
</TEXT>
