<FIRST>r a PM-HarvardLawDean     02-17 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Harvard Law Dean,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper: New Harvard Law Dean to be Named</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harvard University President Derek Bok is
set to name corporate law professor Robert C. Clark to be the next
dean of Harvard Law School, the Harvard Crimson reported today.
   A professor at the university since 1978, Clark would succeed
James Vorenberg, 49, who last year announced his intention to step
down.
   Citing unidentified professors, the student newspaper said Clark
was among three or four candidates referred by a six-member faculty
committee to Bok to be the next dean.
   One professor said the appointment was scheduled to be announced
next Wednesday, ``but it will probably be speeded up'' now that the
information is out.
   Clark was originally a member of the faculty committee but
reportedly stepped down last winter when he learned he was a
candidate for the post.
   Clark, 44, has a bachelor's degree from the Maryknoll Seminary, a
doctorate from Columbia and a law degree from Harvard, the Crimson
reported.
   He was an associate with the Ropes and Gray law firm in Boston
from 1972 to 1974 before becoming a professor at Yale Law School. He
accepted a post at Harvard in 1978.
