<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia     02-17 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebel Leader Fires Senior Officers For Disloyalty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH L. WHITING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of the smallest faction
fighting Vietnam's occupation of Cambodia today said he dismissed
his guerrilla commander and other senior officers for lack of
discipline and disloyalty.
   The leader of the smallest rebel faction, Son Sann, said he was
taking over the military command of his Khmer People's National
Liberation Front. It was the latest in a series of internal disputes
that have seriously weakened his force in recent years.
   He made the announcement to reporters covering the preparations
for the second round of talks aimed at settling the war between
Cambodian guerrillas and Vietnamese troops who invaded Cambodia 10
years ago.
   He said he dismissed Gen. Sak Sutsakhan, the chief of the general
staff and other officers after field commanders accused them of
lacking loyalty and discipline.
   In Hanoi, the official Vietnam News Agency quoted a Foreign
Ministry spokesman as saying Vietnam will ``do its utmost'' to make
the Jakarta talks a success.
   But it quoted the unidentified spokesman as saying Thursday that
the guerrillas demanded the dissolution of the pro-Vietnamese
government in Cambodia ``in disregard of the realities.''
   The guerrillas ``have no foothold'' in Cambodia and ``are losing
support from the outside,'' the Vietnamese spokesman claimed,
according to the dispatch.
   Conflicts already had surfaced in Thursday's preparatory
discussions in Jakarta for weekend talks that include Vietnam and
the government it installed in Cambodia.
   The full talks to begin Sunday will bring together the leaders or
foreign ministers of Vietnam, Laos, the four warring Cambodian
factions, and the Association of Southeast Asian Nations _
Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore, Thailand, Brunei and the Philippines.
   All parties involved say they agree that a future Cambodia should
be independent and neutral. All endorse a government consisting of
the four Cambodian factions and led by Prince Norodom Sihanouk, a
resistance leader.
   They disagree over who would supervise a general election.
   Son Sann refused today to say how many troops his faction had,
but Western diplomats in Thailand put the figure at 13,000.
   The group has been torn by internal power struggles and a
weakened military position since a 1984-85 Vietnamese offensive
wiped out all its major bases along the Thai-Cambodian border.
   Son Sann's group and that of Sihanouk, with an estimated 19,000
fighters, are allied in the resistance coalition with the communist
Khmer Rouge, which has 30,000-40,000 fighters. Some 60,000-70,000
Vietnamese troops remain in Cambodia.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in late 1978 and ended a Khmer Rouge
regime under which about 2 million of Cambodia's 8 million people
died from executions, famine and civil unrest.
   Many nations are concerned the Khmer Rouge may try to reseize
power.
   Hanoi has promised to pull out by 1990, or by September if a
political solution is reached.
</TEXT>
