<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Libya     02-17 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Libya,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toshiba Says It Supplied Equipment For Suspect Libyan Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's Toshiba Corp. provided electrical equipment
for a Libyan factory that the U.S. government suspects of producing
shells for chemical weapons, a Toshiba official said today.
   But the official said Toshiba thought the factory was a
desalination plant, and acted only as subcontractor for Japan Steel
Works, a frequent Toshiba customer.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Japan
Steel Works ordered power transformers and switching equipment for
the plant from Toshiba in June 1985, and Toshiba delivered the
equipment to the company in Japan in December of the same year.
   The equipment is a key component of electrical power systems in
virtually all factories, he said.
   ``We had heard that the equipment would be taken to Libya, but
understood that it would be used in a desalination project,'' the
official said.
   But he said such equipment is normally examined by company
employees after it is installed, and said Toshiba was ``still
examining'' what happened when Toshiba employees checked the suspect
plant. The results of that examination should be known next week, he
said.
   The Japanese government determined in spring 1987 that a Toshiba
subsidiary, Toshiba Machine Co., violated international trade rules
by selling sophisticated milling machines to the Soviet Union that
were capable of manufacturing quieter propellors for Soviet
submarines. Toshiba said then that it was unaware of its
subsidiary's activities.
   Japan Steel Works has denied it helped construct a chemical
weapons plant or provided any weapons-making products to Libya, and
said it only exported desalinization equipment and maintenance
machinery for the suspect factory in Rabta, a desert area near
Tripoli.
   Officials from Japan's trade and foreign ministries also have
denied any Japanese involvement in production of a chemical weapons
plant in Libya.
</TEXT>
