<FIRST>r a PM-CourthouseCops     02-17 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Courthouse Cops,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Files Lawsuit Over Worsening Conditions For Officers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police say the growing number of drug-related
arrests in the city has led to longer waits in booking and
arraigning suspects, with some officers complaining of spending more
than 30 hours processing offenders.
   ``I'm not going to say it's the worst it's ever been, but there
is a backlog everywhere in the system,'' Inspector John P. Walsh,
commander of the Police Department's Criminal Justice Bureau,
conceded Thursday. ``It's simply a volume problem.''
   Although the officers are paid overtime for their waiting, the
Patrolmen's Benevolent Association has filed a lawsuit against the
Police Department, claiming that conditions are ``dangerous,
unsanitary and overcrowded'' for officers forced to wait for hours
in Manhattan's Criminal Courts Building, Queens Central Booking and
Brooklyn Central Booking at the Men's House of Detention.
   The lawsuit was filed last month in state Supreme Court in
Manhattan. A hearing is scheduled next week.
   ``Sure we like the overtime, but to be dehumanized like this,
it's like blood money,'' said one officer who said he had been
waiting 30 hours.
   ``The criminals we bring in get three meals a day and a place to
sleep,'' said another.
   One detective who had arrested a pickpocket in Queens and spent
39 hours waiting for the arrest to be processed said, ``If I had it
to do again I'd let the guy walk away.''
   The officers all declined to give their names.
   Walsh blamed the problem on a significant increase in arrests in
the past year, largely because of drug-related crimes. Citywide
arrests increased 30.4 percent last month over January 1988, from
18,671 to 24,352.
   He said the additional arrests meant that the District Attorney's
office in each borough had more cases and that officers had to wait
longer for interviews with prosecutors in areas with limited space.
   Phil Caruso, head of the police union, said conditions had become
intolerable over the past year and the lawsuit was a last resort.
</TEXT>
