<FIRST>r i PM-NorthernIreland     02-17 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northern Ireland,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunman In Northern Ireland Injures Ex-Soldier and Woman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man shot and slightly wounded
an ex-soldier and a bystander today on a Northern Ireland street,
police said.
   The former soldier, a Protestant who served part-time in the
locally recruited Ulster Defense Regiment until three years ago, was
hit in the arm, police said. A woman was hit with a stray bullet in
the leg, they said.
   The incident happened on the main street of Ballynahinch, 20
miles south of Belfast. There was no immediate claim of
responsibility.
   The gunman escaped in a car that had been hijacked outside a
house in Catholic west Belfast, a stronghold of Irish Republican
Army support, police said. The occupants of the house were held
hostage overnight and then freed.
   On Thursday, gunmen burst into a Protestant barroom in Belfast
and shot and wounded five customers, one of them critically, police
said. The Irish National Liberation Army, an IRA offshoot, claimed
responsibility, saying it was avenging the killing of Catholics in
recent days by Protestant extremists.
   These victims included an attorney specializing in defending IRA
suspects, a town councilor representing the IRA's political wing,
Sinn Fein, and a Belfast glazier with no known political connections.
   The IRA and Irish National Liberation Army are fighting to rid
Northern Ireland of British rule and unite the province and its
Protestant majority with the mainly Catholic Irish Republic. The
Protestant assailants come from shadowy illegal groups committed to
keeping Northern Ireland British.
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary, the province's police force,
issued a statement denouncing the latest ``vicious cycle of violence
and counter violence.''
   It called Catholic and Protestant gunmen ``an evil scourge of
Northern Ireland'' and appealed to the public to reject them and
support the security forces. ``Experience has shown that violence
only begets more violence and produces more grief and misery for
all,'' it said.
