<FIRST>r i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   02-17 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0488,0545</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rabin Proposes Talks With Arabs Toward A `Political Entity'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with reports of clashes today
and army confirming death Thursday. Pickup 8th graf pvs, ``Aides to...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin has proposed
talks with elected Palestinians on forming a ``political entity,''
and offered to hold elections in the occupied lands.
   Rabin, speaking Thursday on Israel's Arabic television, promised
he would bring his proposal to a Cabinet vote if Palestinians in the
territories accepted it, even with reservations. He said army troops
might be withdrawn from the occupied lands on voting days.
   ``We recognize in you a possibility of a political entity,''
Rabin told Palestinians. ``Let us be partners for peace.''
   Rabin did not elaborate on what he meant by a ``political
entity,'' but his wording seemed to suggest he was expanding on the
idea of limited Palestinian self-rule or autonomy once offered by
Israel.
   In the occupied territories Thursday, Israeli soldiers shot and
killed a 25-year-old Palestinian, Issam El Bulbul, during a
stone-throwing clash in the occupied West Bank town of Nablus, Arab
doctors said. Eight Palestinians were wounded in clashes in the West
Bank and occupied Gaza Strip.
   The army said El Bulbul ``intended to throw a large brick at a
soldier'' when he was shot.
   Nablus residents staged a one-day general strike today to protest
his death, which brought to 381 the number of Palestinians killed in
the 14-month rebellion against Israeli rule. Fifteen Israelis have
also been killed.
   In clashes today, two Palestinians were wounded in the West Bank,
Arab hospital officials said. The army confirmed one casualty.
   On Thursday, Israeli legislators, including one from the
center-left Labor Party, caused new tensions in Israel's coalition
government when they met with a prominent Palestinian activist.
   Aides to Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir of the right-wing Likud
bloc said the recent dialogue between some Israelis and Palestinians
linked to the PLO could reignite violence in the occupied lands and
only strengthened the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Labor leader Shimon Peres expressed support for the meetings of
his party members with Palestinians and indicated he would join at a
later stage despite the opposition of party hawks.
   ``I support meetings with the representatives of Palestinians
from the territories who are not involved in terrorism,'' Peres said
on Israel Army radio. ``When I have time I'll meet them too.''
   Two widely publicized meetings took place earlier this week in
Jerusalem involving three prominent pro-PLO figures and leading
Labor members.
   On Thursday, Amnon Rubinstein, head of the centrist Shinui party
and Labor legislator Avraham Burg met Faisal Husseini, the head of
Jerusalem's Arab Studies Center who is closely identified with the
PLO.
   But a growing uproar over the meeting prompted two reserve army
generals, Shlomo Gazit and Aharon Yariv, to back out.
   Husseini, 48, who has been held in detention during most of the
uprising, said he joined in the talks to explain the PLO's positions
to the Israelis.
   ``It's time to go and talk to these people, and let them see the
monster face to face, and see he is not a monster,'' Husseini said.
