<FILEID>AP-NR-02-17-89 0854EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-TaxConfusion     02-17 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tax Confusion,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey Finds Tax Pros Get Wrong Answers, Too</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty professional tax-return preparers came up
with 50 different answers when asked to calculate the federal taxes
of a hypothetical family, Money magazine reported today.
   The professionals' answers ranged from $12,359 to $35,813 _ an
even worse performance than a year ago.
   The accountant who designed the test said the correct tax was
$23,393, but the law is so confusing that several correct answers
were possible, Money said. Ten of the 50 preparers made no major
mistakes but computed the family's taxes as high as $24,493.
   ``The abundance of mistakes our test turned up suggests that pros
are nowhere near as knowledgeable about the tax law as they are
supposed to be,'' Money said in its March issue. ``After all, we
were samplying highly regarded preparers who willingly accepted our
challenge to calculate the model return.''
   The survey suggests that it is not only Internal Revenue Service
employees who are not fully up to speed on provisions of the
landmark 1986 tax overhaul. A General Accounting Office survey
released last week found that IRS personnel whose job is to answer
taxpayers' telephoned queries gave the correct answers to only 64
percent of selected test questions that were posed during the last
filing season.
   The hypothetical family in the magazine survey was one with
problems that, while possible among those with high incomes, are
unlikely to be encountered by the typical taxpayer.
   The family had salaries of $56,400 but both spouses took lump-sum
withdrawals from their pensions after quitting their jobs last year.
The wife started her own business and the husband spent the second
half of the year negotiating to buy his own company. They had a
variety of investments, owned two homes and were willed a third home
by the wife's mother, who died during the year.
   A year ago, Money magazine asked 50 professional return preparers
to figure the taxes of a make-believe family. Then, too, they came
up with 50 different answers and their bottom-line figures varied by
as much as 50 percent.
   ``What's their excuse this year?'' the magazine asked.
   Wesley R. Fitzpatrick, a partner in the Portland, Ore., office of
Grant Thornton accountants, who designed this year's test, said he
was completedly surprised by the results.
   ``When the tax-reform law was new, you could understand the
confusion, but now it's hard to explain all the mistakes about
fundamental rules,'' Fitzpatrick said.
   The survey found that some of the professionals failed to ask the
right questions when they encontered something confusing about the
hypothetical family's finances. The GAO said that same shortcoming
was to blame for many of the mistakes made by the IRS people who
answer telephoned questions.
   Money's survey involved 30 certified public accountants, 12
preparers from franchise tax-preparation operations, three CPAs from
national accounting firms and five enrolled agents, who are
IRS-licensed tax-return preparers.
   Returns free of major mistakes were prepared by five CPAs not
affiliated with national companies, one enrolled agent, three
preparers from franchise outlets, and Fitzpatrick, the CPA who
devised the test.
   Money noted that the survey was conducted before much of the
computer software widely used in the business was ready for this
year's returns. ``In all probability, the computers would have
performed somewhat better than the preparers' pencils and
calculators, although Fitzpatrick maintains that software would not
have caught the most common mistakes,'' the magazine said.
   Although the hypothetical family had financial situations that
most Americans are not likely to encounter, the professional tax
preparers made mistakes in areas that are far more common. For
example, 16 of the 50 failed to note that the family's 13-year-old
son would be required to file a return because he earned $600 mowing
lawns.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
