<FIRST>r a PM-WrongBody     02-17 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wrong Body,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gravediggers Exhume Wrong Bodies For Murder Investigators</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gravediggers ordered to exhume the corpse of a
man who may have been murdered apparently dug up the wrong body
twice and aren't sure where to dig next, a cemetery owner says.
   The Baltimore state's attorney's office ordered the exhumation of
the Rev. Rayfield Gilliard, 77, who died last year two weeks after
marrying a woman subsequently charged with killing four other people
for their life insurance benefits. Detectives want an autopsy to see
if he, too, was slain.
   The first body, removed in December from a pauper's grave at
Mount Zion Cemetery in Landsdowne just south of Baltimore, was
actually examined in an autopsy before someone noticed the
identification tag on it. The body didn't even resemble Gilliard,
said cemetery manager Samuel Brown.
   ``The body was a real thin, skinny man,'' Brown said. ``Mr.
Gilliard was a heavy-set man with big, full face.''
   Brown said his records wrongly indicated that Gilliard's body was
in row 83. After the mistake was discovered, Brown said he realized
Gilliard actually should be in row 78.
   Several weeks later, another body was exhumed. But a detective at
the grave found a toe tag with another man's name on it, so the body
was reburied.
   ``The detective couldn't make out the name on the tag. It was
W-I-L something. So we put the body back,'' Brown said.
   But Brown said he's not convinced the second body wasn't Gilliard.
   ``The detective showed me a picture of Mr. Gilliard, and when we
dug up the second coffin that guy looked exactly like Mr.
Gilliard,'' he said. ``Whoever embalmed him did a good job.''
   Joseph Russ, who owns the cemetery, promised Thursday ``to do our
best to find'' Gilliard's body. He blamed the erroneous burial
records on inexperienced cemetery workers.
   Police say the woman Gilliard married on Jan. 18, 1988, is
Geraldine Parrish, 52, who is accused of orchestrating four slayings
to collect the victims' insurance payments.
   Gilliard died 15 days after the wedding, leaving his $440 a month
in Social Security benefits, his home and about $1,000 to his wife.
   The death certificate said he died of arteriosclerotic
cardiovascular disease, a type of heart disease. But the Rev.
Alphonso Thompson, who married the couple, said that Gilliard didn't
have heart trouble as far as he knew.
   Last summer, Ms. Parrish was indicted and jailed, charged in four
deaths and three attempts to kill a fifth person. Police seized 45
insurance policies from locked closets and safes at Ms. Parrish's
home.
</TEXT>
