<FILEID>AP-NR-02-17-89 0950EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AIDSDiscrimination     02-17 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Discrimination,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman With AIDS Virus Wins Fight Against Beauty Salons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state hearing examiner has ordered two beauty
salons to serve a woman they turned away because she was infected
with the AIDS virus.
   The consent order, coming two years after Tema Luft, 36, was
turned away by the salons, preliminarily establishes the legal
principle that people with AIDS-related illnesses are protected by
Maryland's anti-discrimination laws.
   ``This sends a message to businesses that are discriminating or
might discriminate that if they do so, they are going to be charged
with violating state law,'' Lee Hoshall, a lawyer for the state
Human Relations Commission, said Thursday.
   Under the consent order approved Tuesday by a hearing examiner
for the commission, the Nail Gallery in Reisterstown and All that
Glitters in Pikesville agreed to serve Ms. Luft and others infected
with the AIDS virus.
   The case marked the first time a hearing examiner ruled that a
state law protecting handicapped people from discrimination applies
to people infected with the virus that causes acquired immune
deficiency syndrome.
   The consent order averts a quasi-judicial hearing on the
complaint.
   Ms. Luft, a C&amp;P Telephone Co. employee who contracted the AIDS
virus in 1985, said the settlement may not change attitudes toward
the disease but will at least give infected individuals legal
ammunition if they are faced with discrimination.
   She said she was unsure whether she would return to the salons
for service.
   Both salons had served Ms. Luft until she made a televised
appearance at an AIDS conference.
   ``My clients are naturally glad the case is over,'' said Thomas
Bowden, attorney for the owners of All That Glitters. ``They hold no
grudge about Tema and cetainly wish her well in dealing with her
illness.''
   A woman answering the phone at the Nail Gallery today said she
was the owner but would not comment on the ruling or give her name.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
