<SECOND>PM-China-Art Exhibit,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Troubled Exhibit of Modern Art Reopens in Beijing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A controversial exhibition of avant-garde art
reopened today under tight security, two days after police closed it
because of a bomb threat.
   The show was also closed on opening day, Feb. 5, for five days
when artists defied a ban on performance art and one fired two BBs
into her sculpture.
   Uniformed guards patrolled the three floors of the China Art
Gallery today as crowds of mainly young people gathered in front of
the paintings and sculptures. Guards were posted at the main gate of
the museum, and no bags or large packages were allowed inside.
   Police closed the show Wednesday after a Beijing newspaper
received a letter saying bombs would be planted in the gallery if
the show was not shut for good. Organizers said they believe an
artist was responsible for the threat, which they view as a hoax.
   ``It seems to be another kind of performance art,'' said one
organizer. ``We think the artist is trying to show art's
relationship with Chinese society.''
   On Feb. 5, a series of performance art pieces culminating in the
shooting of a telephone booth sculpture by the artist led
authorities to close the show. The artist and her boyfriend were
detained for three days and then released.
   The show is the largest avant-garde show in China's history,
filling five large halls of the China Art Gallery with more than 250
works. It is the first large-scale exhibition of Chinese modern art
to be held in Beijing since 1981.
</TEXT>
