<FIRST>r a PM-ProstituteKillings     02-17 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prostitute Killings,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Investigate Wave of Prostitute Slayings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A serial killer is preying on prostitutes in
the same crime-infested area that gave rise to the Southside Slayer,
and may have killed as many as 12 women, authorities said.
   ``I will confirm that an investigation is currently being
conducted on female victims who were engaged in prostitution for
drugs,'' said police Lt. Fred Nixon, a department spokesman.
   Police Lt. John Zorn, who is coordinating the latest
investigation, said Thursday that at least nine of the most recent
victims were killed with the same weapon.
   ``There's one gun. They have one weapon used over and over,''
Zorn said. ``It's a small handgun. This type and caliber of handgun
has been targeted by the department.''
   ``You don't know there's one killer until several deaths occur,''
Zorn said. ``Once they make the connection and see the same gun,
they realize they have the same suspect.''
   Television station KABC reported Thursday that as many as 12
prostitutes have been found shot to death in the area since August
1985.
   Zorn also headed the task force that investigated the so-called
Southside Slayer Task Force, whose victims were found strangled in
South Central Los Angeles between September 1983 and July 1986. Most
of them had been stabbed, and all but a few had arrest records for
prostitution.
   One man has been convicted of one of the slayings and two others
were charged separately in seven of the killings.
   KABC said police have been quietly investigating the latest
string of killings for a year, which drew criticism from community
activist Margaret Prescod, who called such a low-profile approach
outrageous.
   ``It feels as though history is repeating itself,'' she said.
``Eleven women were already murdered before they called the press
conference to tell us about the Southside Slayer.''
   KABC said the investigation had been kept quiet because of fears
that publicity would bring protests from residents, but Nixon denied
that was the case.
   ``Our reluctance to publicize the killings has nothing to do with
a fear of any major demonstrations,'' he said.
   Police added they are warning women who fit the profile of those
murdered to be cautious.
   Nixon said the victims are called ``strawberries'' in street
jargon because they sell sex for drugs, but declined to give further
background on them.
</TEXT>
