<FIRST>r a PM-HotelFire 1stLd-Writethru a0517 02-17 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hotel Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0517,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Die In Detroit Hotel Fire; More Than 40 Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Rewrites throughout to update with four deaths, arsons suspected,
people escaped down makeshift ropes, quotes, Adds byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRETEL WIKLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A four-alarm fire broke out early today in a
downtown hotel, killing at least four people and forcing some
residents to slide down makeshift ropes of blankets and sheets in
freezing weather, officials said.
   Fire officials said arson was suspected.
   At least 52 people were sent to hospitals. Four police officers
trying to evacuate the residential hotel were among the injured.
   The fire was discovered at 3:12 a.m. at the Billinghurst Hotel by
police Sgt. John Stevenson, who was on routine patrol, police
spokesman Sgt. Christopher Buck said.
   Buck said Stevenson got one resident out of the building, called
the fire department, then went back in to alert other residents.
   Temperatures were in the teens while some residents tied sheets
and blankets together to slide from their windows down the
five-story building's walls.
   Aubrey Chappell, 25, said he was awakened in his second-story
room by the smell of smoke.
   ``Then I opened the door and I couldn't breathe,'' he said. ``I
went to the window, tied sheets (together), grabbed my credentials
and climbed out.''
   ``There were quite a few jumpers, as you can see these sheets
hanging out of windows,'' said Deputy Fire Chief Salvatore Finazzo.
   Authorities suspect an arsonist started the blaze on the hotel's
first floor, Finazzo said, but he refused to elaborate.
   Residents and fire officials estimated 130 to 200 people, most
welfare recipients, lived in the brick hotel.
   The building had no sprinkler system, but some residents said
they heard smoke alarms sounding.
   Buck said the identities and cause of death of the four dead
people were unconfirmed. The injured were taken to four hospitals.
   Buck said at least three of the hurt, some of whom were injured
while jumping out of windows, were in critical condition.
   The injured officers suffered from smoke inhalation, broken bones
and other injuries. Their conditions were unknown.
</TEXT>
