<DOCNO> AP890217-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-17-89 1138EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines     02-17 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Urban Rebels Plan To Kill Five People A Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist guerrillas operating in the
nation's cities say they plan to kill five people a month in their
fight against the government, according to a report published today.
   Also today, the military reported that 21 people were killed
Thursday in clashes between government troops and communist rebels.
   The tabloid People's Journal Tonight today reproduced a crudely
scribbled note the newspaper said it received Thursday from the Alex
Boncayao Brigade, or ABB, the urban assassination unit of the
communist New People's Army.
   ``Five officials a month is our quota,'' said the note, which was
signed ``ABB-Jomar Squad.'' An accompanying article said that
shortly before the note was delivered, a man claiming to be a rebel
spokesman telephoned the newspaper's office with the same message.
   On Wednesday, four men gunned down a constabulary intelligence
officer in the Manila suburb of Malabon and left a note signed
``A.B.B.-Jomar Squad.''
   A military officer and an enlisted man were shot to death Monday
on Manila's outskirts by suspected rebels. One of the assailants
also was killed in the gunfire. The Alex Boncayao Brigade claimed
responsibility.
   In one of the military attacks Thursday, 10 soldiers and a
civilian cook were killed when 200 New People's Army rebels fired on
two army trucks packed with troops in Misamis Occidental province,
the military said.
   The soldiers were disembarking from their trucks in Calamba
municipality, 450 miles southeast of Manila, when the rebels opened
fire, the report said.
   It said scores of people were injured and that the bodies of
eight guerrillas were found after a firefight of several hours.
   Also Thursday, rebels sprayed a constabulary patrol car with
bullets in the town of San Simon in Pampanga province, 30 miles
north of Manila, and killed one soldier, another military report
said.
   A rebel also was killed in the attack, the report said.
</TEXT>
