<FIRST>u a PM-FloodRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0489 02-17 0711</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flood Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0489,0726</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kentucky, Tennessee Get Respite From Rain, But More May Be On Way</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 18 grafs to UPDATE with some waters receding although
other rivers still rising, three deaths in Texas, states could get more
rain from storm now in Texas, damage assessment beginning in Tennessee
communities, other details. Pickup 16th graf, `On Thursday...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Flood waters began to recede in parts of Tennessee and Kentucky
but the mighty Ohio and other rivers rose today after a week of
unrelenting rain flooded homes and forced the evacuation of hundreds
of residents.
   A central Kentucky town became an island when swirling, muddy
water encapsuled it Thursday. The only way out was by boat or
helicopter. Three people were killed and a child was missing after
their car was swept away in a rain-swollen creek near Mineral Wells,
Texas.
   Tennessee Gov. Ned McWherter asked the U.S. Small Business
Administration on Thursday to designate eight middle Tennessee
counties as flood disaster areas. Kentucky officials said they would
seek similar federal relief.
   ``We hope the worst of it is over,'' Kentucky Gov. Wallace
Wilkinson said after touring some of the hardest-hit areas of his
state.
   Although the rain let up Thursday, Cecil Whaley, an operations
officer for the Tennessee Emergency Management Agency, said today
that forecasters were watching a storm in Texas expected to move
into the state.
   ``It appears to be headed toward us. ... Either Kentucky or
Tennessee will get a lot of moisture. We just don't know who it's
going to be,'' he said.
   A week's worth of rainfall, measuring more than 10 inches in some
places, flooded roads, forced schools to close and claimed at least
three lives.
   Kentucky officials estimated that at least 1,000 people were
forced from their homes by rising waters in most of the river
systems in the western two-thirds of the state.
   The Kentucky River crested today at 44.2 feet _ more than 13 feet
above flood stage _ at Frankfort in central Kentucky, and several
other rivers and streams also began receding, the National Weather
Service said. However, the Ohio and Green rivers were still rising
slightly and could force some river levels higher again, said
forecaster Mike Callahan in Louisville.
   In Tennessee, officials said Valentine's Day flooding in Wilson
County damaged 66 businesses and 28 homes around the city of
Lebanon, causing an estimated $1.9 million in damage.
   The rain-swollen Obion River burst through a levee in rural Obion
County early Thursday, sending a three-foot wall of water through
the towns of Rives and Obion, forcing 377 people from their homes,
officials said.
   At least 43 homes, seven mobile homes, two churches and a fire
station were saturated with water after the levee burst, said Whaley.
   ``A lot of the homes had up to 50 percent damage,'' he said. ``It
could be quite a while before they get back into them.''
   Whaley said the river had begun receding and damage assessment
would begin today.
   Flood waters turned the riverside community of Boston, Ky.,
population 400, into an island. The Rolling Fork of the Salt River
neared a crest of 52 feet today, three-tenths of a foot over its
previous record high.
   Conditions in Boston won't improve significantly until the Ohio
crests at Louisville, 23 miles north, Callahan said today.
   ``We're locked in,'' said Joe Sims, 35. ``It's the nearest thing
to suffocating.''
   All roads were blocked and residents couldn't even walk out.
   On Thursday, people strolled in the sunshine _ the first break
from rain in four days _ and picked up supplies at the town's only
open store, all the while warily eying the waters that were still
rising.
   ``We've got plenty of food. As long as nobody gets sick, we're
all right,'' said Betty Vandiver, who has lived in Boston for 32
years.
   Disaster officials in Kentucky said they hoped to have enough
information compiled today to make a preliminary request for federal
aid. Assistance could include low-interest loans and special
attention from federal relief programs.
   Chuck Bogart, a spokesman for the Division of Disaster and
Emergency Services, said firm figures on the actual damage caused by
the flooding will not be available until the waters recede.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
