<HEAD>Grenade Attack Kills Black Policeman, Injures Nine</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: New thruout to CORRECT that 10 officers involved, sted nine.
No pickup.</UNK>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five hand grenades were tossed
at a group of black police officers, killing one and injuring nine,
officials said today.
   Police said the attack occurred Thursday night in Kathlehong, a
black township east of Johannesburg.
   In Carletonville, 45 miles southwest of Johannesburg, blacks were
considering a boycott of white businesses in response to beatings of
blacks who venture out after dark, according to a report published
today.
   In the bombing incident, 10 special constables _ blacks assigned
to police duty in townships after shorter-than-normal training
periods _ were standing in a railway yard when one or more
assailants hurled five hand grenades, police said. Constable W.S.
Tladi was killed and nine officers were injured, two seriously,
police said.
   A similar attack occurred in Kathlehong Jan. 5, when one black
police officer was killed and 31 injured by a grenade thrown while
they were on parade. There was no claim of responsibility for either
attack.
   Police have blamed the outlawed African National Congress
guerrilla movement for virtually all of the numerous attacks on
black officers, who are viewed by many black activists as
collaborators with the white government.
   The country's largest-circulation black newspaper, City Press,
reported that blacks in the mining town of Carletonville planned a
consumer boycott to protest beatings by whites of blacks seen on
local streets after dark.
   The town council is controlled by the extreme-right Conservative
Party and has proposed a curfew that would bar blacks from the town
center at night.
   A decision on the proposal is expected by the end of the month.
City Press said black activists would meet Sunday to discuss a
boycott.
</TEXT>
