<FIRST>r i PM-SAfrica-Press     02-17 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Press,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Anti-Apartheid Publications Banned for Three Months</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today banned two
anti-apartheid publications for three months after accusing them of
repeatedly publishing subversive material.
   The publications, based in Cape Town and affiliated with each
other, are Grassroots, a monthly tabloid newspaper, and New Era, a
quarterly magazine.
   Three other anti-apartheid publications were banned for varying
periods last year under state-of-emergency regulations which give
broad censorship powers to Home Affairs Minister Stoffel Botha.
   He said Grassroots and New Era had carried articles ``promoting
revolution, stirring up hatred towards the security forces, and
promoting the public esteem of unlawful organizations, such as the
African National Congress.''
   The outlawed African National Congress is the leading group
fighting the South African system of apartheid, which enshrines
control by 5 million whites over a country with 26 million blacks.
   Grassroots was established in 1980 and distributes 50,000 copies
throughout the Cape Town region. New Era, a younger publication,
circulates 5,000 copies nationwide.
   In a statement responding to the banning, the staff of Grassroots
said: ``Today is a tragic one for the people of the Western Cape.''
   ``Our fate has been predetermined by an individual minister whose
subjective opinion cannot be challenged in a court of law,'' it
said. ``On May 17, we will back, and we will be continuing to
publish the truth.''
</TEXT>
