<FIRST>r a PM-PoliceRacism     02-17 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Police Racism,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Racial Slurs Sent Via Police Computers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAWTHORNE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police officers in at least four
departments have used the mobile computer terminals in their patrol
cars to transmit racial and other slurs, authorities said.
   Police Chief Kenneth Stonebraker said three officers in his
department were disciplined for two incidents that have occurred
since 1986, and a third incident last weekend was still under
investigation.
   Robert Benson, executive director of the police communications
center that recorded the exchanges, said Thursday that officers at
the three other police departments the center serves _ Manhattan
Beach, Gardena and El Segundo _ have transmitted similar messages
over their computers in the last several years.
   The first incident reported in Hawthorne came to light earlier
this week when computer printouts kept at the communications center
were leaked to television station KCBS. They showed officers
transmitting racial, anti-homosexual and anti-Semitic jokes.
   ``They're inappropriate. There's no way to justify them,''
Stonebraker said. But he added he doesn't believe the three
incidents represent a festering problem within the department.
   Officers are told during training that computer printouts are
routinely kept of their computer exchanges, Stonebraker said.
   None of the officers has been identified.
   Jim Martin, western regional manager of the National Association
for the Advancement of Colored People, called the incident
``extremely troubling.''
   ``The messages tell us blacks are not welcome in that
community,'' he said.
   Police Sgt. Don Jackson, who is on a stress-disability leave from
the Hawthorne department that he says was brought on by racial
discrimination, declined to comment on the messages.
   Jackson, who is black, recently set up a videotaped sting
operation against Long Beach police he said was designed to see if
charges of racism within that department were true.
   The videotape, broadcast nationally, shows a white officer
apparently slamming Jackson's head through a plate glass window
during a traffic stop.
</TEXT>
