<FIRST>u i PM-SAfrica-HungerStrike     02-17 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Hunger Strike,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Detainees End Hunger Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 detainees in a
Port Elizabeth prison ended a 3-week-old hunger strike today after
being told of a government promise to free some blacks being held
without charge.
   The decision by 105 detainees at St. Albans Prison was announced
by attorney Kobus Pienaar. It followed a decision Thursday by 170
detainees at a Johannesburg prision to end their hunger strike. An
undetermined number of other detainees continued their strike at
other prisons around South Africa.
   Prominent anti-apartheid detainees, including some who have been
hospitalized from the effects of the strike, were freed while
attorneys met with the minister of law and order aimed at more
releases.
   Trevor Manuel, regional director of the United Democratic Front
in the Cape Town area, was freed from Pollsmoor Prison, his lawyer's
office said. Manuel had not been part of the hunger strike that
began at Diepkloof prison outside Johannesburg on Jan. 23 and spread
to other prisons and jails in the country.
   Manuel had been detained since October. He previously had been
detained from August 1986 through July 1988.
   When Manuel was freed in July, he was ordered not to talk to
journalists, criticize the government, or participate in any
activities of the now-banned UDF, which was the nation's largest
anti-apartheid group.
   It was not immediately known if any restrictions were placed on
Manuel in connection with his release today.
   The minister of law and order, Adriaan Vlok, said Thursday a
``substantial number'' of the estimated 1,000 blacks in custody
without charge would be released within two weeks, but he said some
would be placed under restrictions.
   None has been charged with a crime, but some have been held since
the national state of emergency was declared June 12, 1986.
   Ernest Dube, 26, a member of the Soweto Youth Congress who had
been hospitalized because of his hunger strike, was freed from
custody but remained in Johannesburg Hospital, said the Detainees
Aid Center.
   An attorney who met with Vlok told the South African Press
Association that three other men _ two of them in hospitals _ were
being freed today.
</TEXT>
