<FIRST>u a PM-INS-CentralAmericans 1stLd-Writethru a05(PHILADELPHIA)_ADowningtownmanischarSeekersNearTexas-MexicoBordetlantagacloudy3882e1430.56Dp33rdkbacksduringhis16yearsinoffice.
02-17 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-INS-Central Americans, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0570,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rules INS Can Keep Asylum-Seekers Near Texas-Mexico Border</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 11 grafs with background on case, further details and quotes
from ruling, reaction, appeal filed.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today ruled that the
Immigration and Naturalization Service can reinstate a policy that
confines refugees to South Texas while their applications for
political asylum are considered.
   The decision by U.S. District Judge Filemon Vela denied an
injunction sought by attorneys for refugees who sued the INS over
the no-travel policy.
   The regulation was blamed for a backup of hundreds of homeless
Central Americans at the southern tip of Texas. The judge on Jan. 9
temporarily ordered the INS to allow refugees to travel to their
intended U.S. destinations while he reviewed the request for a
permanent lifting of the no-travel policy.
   Many refugees then boarded buses for California and Florida.
   A report Thursday indicated Central American refugees might be
detained in a South Texas tent city while their applications for
political asylum are processed. U.S. Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, says
the facility would meet basic human necessities of adequate housing,
food and sanitary conditions. There would not be a fence.
   ``We think that's going to create a multitude of problems here in
the (Lower Rio Grande) Valley,'' Mark Schneider, one of the
attorneys who sued the INS over the matter, said after learning of
the judge's decision.
   The attorneys quickly appealed Vela's order. Attorney Linda Yanez
said she filed the appeal in Brownsville and asked for an injunction
against the INS pending that appeal.
   INS officials in Harlingen said they would comment on the ruling
later today.
   More than 100,000 Central Americans are expected to pour into the
area this year, after crossing the Rio Grande illegally near
Brownsville, according to the INS.
   INS officials last spring reported a large increase in the number
of Central Americans seeking political asylum in South Texas. The
agency had stamped asylum-seekers documents and allowed them to
travel to their declared U.S. destinations until Dec. 15, when faced
with huge case backlogs in cities such as Miami and Los Angeles, it
started requiring people to pursue their cases in Harlingen.
   Hundreds of immigrants started camping in squalid conditions in
makeshift tents and condemned buildings in the area, prompting a
local public outcry.
   Attorneys filed a class-action lawsuit against the INS,
contending it failed to seek public comment before making the
change, as required by federal law. The suit prompted Judge Vela to
issue the temporary restraining order that expires Monday.
   Vela today agreed with the INS that public comment was not
required for the travel restriction because it merely constituted
``general statements of agency organization, procedure, or
practice,'' and did not remove the opportunity to apply for asylum.
The changes were ``procedural, rather than substantive,'' Vela said.
   ``The changes merely alter the location of adjudication of the
asylum applications,'' he wrote.
   Asylum is granted to those fleeing various forms of persecution.
The INS contends, however, that most of those seeking asylum come to
the United States only for economic reasons, and therefore do not
qualify for asylum.
   Those suing the agency contend that the asylum-seekers should be
able to travel to cities where they have families and friends and
better access to legal representation while pursuing their cases.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
