<FIRST>r a PM-MoneyLaundering 1stLd-Writethru a0555 02-17 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Money Laundering, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0555,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Head Of Colombian Money Laundering Operation Gets 40 Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT to Medellin, sted Medillin.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Colombian who ran a major
money-laundering operation in the United States for some of the
world's biggest cocaine traffickers has been sentenced to 40 years
in prison.
   Carlos Restrepo, 38, of Medellin, who claims he was engaged in
the legitimate business of currency exchange, said after sentencing
Thursday he would appeal his conviction.
   Restrepo and three other men sentenced with him in U.S. District
Court were arrested in June 1987 after a three-year FBI undercover
investigation. About 100 people around the country turned over $200
million in drug money to FBI agents posing as money launderers, said
U.S. Attorney Stanley Twardy.
   Restrepo was convicted in November of 66 counts, including
multiple violations of the federal Money Laundering and Travel acts,
racketeering and conspiracy.
   He was found to have moved about $13 million in cocaine proceeds
through a dummy corporation set up by the FBI in Greenwich between
September 1986 and June 1987. Prosecutors also presented evidence
that he laundered about $7 million through operations in Los Angeles
and San Francisco.
   Assistant U.S. Attorneys Richard N. Palmer and James T. Cowdery
told the court that the money laundered by Restrepo would purchase
more than 2{ tons of cocaine in Colombia for sale in the United
States.
   Also Thursday Judge Jose Cabranes sentenced Carlos Gaviria, 31,
of Colombia, to 20 years in prison. Gaviria was a lieutenant in an
enterprise that laundered money for the organization of Rigoberto
Correa, the government said.
   Marco Tulio Lora, 50, and Jorge Gomez, 35, Colombians who had
been living in Miami, received 16-year prison sentences. Prosecutors
said they served as brokers in the money-laundering business.
   Three men described as couriers for Restrepo were sentenced
Wednesday. One received a four-year sentence while the others were
placed on probation.
   Restrepo was the only defendant convicted in Connecticut who did
not plead guilty. His attorney, Vincent Flynn, contended that
Restrepo was an innocent businessman involved in currency exchange.
</TEXT>
