<HEAD>Some US Embassy Workers Removed from Beirut by Helicopter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts grafs 3-4 with State Dept. comment; editing changes
to conform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States evacuated some of its
personnel from the embassy in Beirut, Lebanon, this morning, using a
routine helicopter supply flight to move the workers to Cyprus,
defense officials said.
   The officials, who asked not to be identified, said between 13
and 16 diplomatic workers were withdrawn on Army UH-60 Blackhawk
helicopters, leaving about 25 others still at work at the Beirut
embassy.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman confirmed that some
embassy personnel were evacuated but declined to provide figures.
   ``The recent fighting underscores the urgent need for all
Lebanese to work together to restore legitimate national
institutions,'' he said.
   The helicopters are based on Cyprus to provide logistical support
to the embassy because of the uncertainty of access to the war-torn
nation.
   Redman in recent days has reported the embassy has been caught in
a crossfire due to heavy fighting between rival Christian factions.
According to local police, the fighting earlier this week left 69
people dead and 197 wounded.
   The defense sources said today that a Marine amphibious group is
on a routine deployment in the eastern Mediterranean, but they said
it played no role in the evacuation.
   ``At the request of the State Department, we used a normal
logistical flight to remove some of the embassy people,'' said one
source. ``Everything went as planned.''
