<HEAD>Army Commander Threatens To Destroy Christian Militia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to ADD State Dept. comment on safety at embassy,
FIX typo in ``apocalypse'' in lede. Pickup 7th pvs, ``The helicopters...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Lebanon-Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The commander of the Christian-controlled
army said today the nation faces an ``apocalypse'' if fighting
flares up again between his forces and a rival Christian militia.
   Army leader Gen. Michel Aoun, who also heads the Christian
Cabinet in Lebanon's divided government, told a news conference:
   ``We are responsible for the state, and they want a mini-state
.... Those who do not abide by the law, I'll crush their heads.''
   A cease-fire between the army and the Lebanese Forces militia was
reached Wednesday after fierce clashes earlier in the week around
Christian east Beirut left 69 people dead and 197 wounded, according
to police count.
   The State Department says the U.S. Embassy in Beirut was being
caught in the crossfire, and today some personnel were evacuated.
   Defense officials in Washington, who requested anonymity, said
between 13 and 16 diplomatic workers were withdrawn on Army UH-60
Blackhawk helicopters, leaving about 25 others still at work at the
embassy.
   The helicopters are based on Cyprus to provide logistical support
to the embassy because of the uncertainty of access to the war-torn
nation.
   Aoun said today he accepted the cease-fire mediated by the
Maronite Catholic Patriarch Nasrallah Sfeir and hopes efforts to
reach a peaceful settlement will succeed.
   ``Otherwise, it will be total destruction,'' he said. ``This time
it will be apocalypse,'' he said at his heavily-guarded headquarters
in the Yarze suburb, east of Beirut.
   Aoun demanded the rival Christian force withdraw from east Beirut
and accused it of starting this week's fighting. The battles have
deepened divisions in the Christian community in this nation already
rent by years of civil war between Christians and Moslems, who
control a rival government.
   The army commander said his forces thwarted an attack by the
Lebanese Forces on his home in a wealthy section of east Beirut on
Wednesday. He was away in Yarze at the time.
   During the battles this week, Aoun's army captured militia
positions in Lebanon's central mountains. It also broke through some
militia strongholds in east Beirut, but the militia remained in most
residential districts here.
</TEXT>
