<FIRST>r a PM-PavilionFire     02-17 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pavilion Fire,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blaze Guts San Francisco Art Gallery</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATALINA ORTIZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fast-moving five-alarm fire gutted a
prominent art gallery, destroying a collection valued by the artist
at more than $1 million and sending off flames that were visible
throughout most of the city.
   No injuries were reported, but about 1,100 people attending a
concert at the Fillmore Auditorium, adjacent to the Duquette
Pavilion of St. Francis, were evacuated, authorities said.
   ``The interior is all gone,'' Assistant Fire Chief Ed Murphy said
at the scene of the blaze.
   The blaze was controlled at 2:44 a.m., more than five hours after
it was reported. Firefighters were still trying to determine its
cause but Fire Chief Fred Postel said it was believed to have
started in a caretaker's apartment in the six- to seven-story
building, formerly a synagogue. Arson investigator Al Silvestri said
there was nothing suspicious about the fire.
   ``There were flames like I've never seen before,'' said Eddie
Seymour, 18, who lives a few blocks from the gallery, which features
the work of artist and owner Tony Duquette. The fire was visible
from most of the city and acrid smoke blanketed the Western Addition
district and surrounding neighborhoods.
   Buildings adjacent to the gallery, including the famous Fillmore
and the former Peoples Temple run by the Rev. Jim Jones, were not
damaged by flames but may have suffered water damage, Postel said.
   About 140 firefighters battled the fire, which quickly climbed to
the roof of the stately buff brick building. Postel said the
structure's large open interior space and wooden ceiling supported
by trusses instead of columns made it difficult to fight the blaze.
   A shaken Duquette watched as firefighters directed cascades of
water into the building through the shattered stained glass window
and the remains of a metal starburst sculpture that partly covered
it.
   The artist said the collection was valued at more than more $1
million but was too distraught to provide other details. The
collection, which had been featured in Time and other publications,
included tapestries and sculptures, much of it dedicated to St.
Francis of Assisi, the saint for whom San Francisco is named.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
