<FILEID>AP-NR-02-17-89 1251EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--ExplodingToilets     02-17 0156</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Exploding Toilets,0160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toilets Explode After Air Compressor Connected To Water Line</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About two dozen toilets and urinals in the King
County Courthouse exploded when they were flushed because an air
compressor had been erroneously connected to a water line, officials
said.
   ``We think we've lost about 20 to 25 toilets,'' said building
services manager Bill Kemp. ``The porcelain is actually cracked.''
   ``We knew it had to be air in the system, but the (city) Water
Department said that was impossible,'' Kemp said.
   Officials eventually traced Thursday's problem in the 72-year-old
building to an compressor hooked up by a construction worker at a
nearby $430 million bus tunnel project.
   Kemp said no injuries were reported, although several people
apparently were soaked.
   All courthouse restrooms were closed for the rest of the day, and
people had to cross the street to toilets in the county
Administration Building. Damages had not yet been determined.
</TEXT>
