<FIRST>u a PM-Hudson-Reax 2ndLd-Writethru a0544 02-17 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hudson-Reax, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0544,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Critics Say Award In Hudson Case Excessive, Sends Wrong Message</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lede to UPDATE with new total of $21.75 million after jury
added another $7.25 million today; SUBS 3rd graf, `Christian was ...' to
restore first reference to Mark Miller.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hudson Suit, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $21.75 million jury award to Rock Hudson's
lover is ``clearly excessive'' and ``catastrophic,'' critics said,
but others praised the verdict for sending a message about
responsibility to those with AIDS.
   Some lawyers were aghast at the size of the award to Marc
Christian, and one homosexual rights activist said he was concerned
that the decision would wrongly free lovers of their responsibility
to protect themselves against AIDS.
   Christian was Hudson's homosexual lover before the actor died of
AIDS on Oct. 5, 1985. Christian sued Hudson's estate and personal
secretary, Mark Miller, saying they had caused him emotional anguish
by failing to warn him that Hudson had the fatal disease.
   Jurors found Hudson and Miller engaged in ``outrageous conduct''
by failing to tell Christian of Hudson's diagnosis.
   Benjamin Schatz, a lawyer for National Gay Rights Advocates in
San Francisco, said the case ``sends a dangerous message. It tells
people that if they continue to bury their heads in the sand by
engaging in unsafe sex and become infected, it's entirely their
partner's fault and they don't bear any responsibility.''
   ``While we understand the jury's sympathy for the plaintiff, the
precedent their award establishes is catastrophic,'' said Frank
Schubert, president of the Association for California Tort Reform.
``What the jury's done is award damages for fear, whether it's
rational fear or not.''
   Christian consistently has tested negative for infection with the
AIDS virus. His lawyer said that's no guarantee he won't eventually
develop AIDS because of his sexual liaisons with Hudson.
   Under California law, the issue is irrelevant, said attorney
Margaret Davis, author of ``Lovers, Doctors &amp; the Law,'' and Tom
Coleman, legal director for the Gay and Lesbian Community Services
Center in Los Angeles.
   ``In (many) other jurisdictions, you have to show physical injury
as well as emotional injury,'' Ms. Davis said. ``In California, if
you can prove ... emotional distress, you do not have to prove a
tangible injury.''
   Coleman said the jury was right to side with Christian, but
added: ``The damages seem a bit high ... when you compare it with
someone who may be paralyzed for life and may get a lot less money.''
   Ms. Davis said the ``larger-than-anticipated'' award ``sends a
really serious symbolic message to all lovers. The person who is
going to mislead a sexual partner is really going to think twice
before they tell a lie.''
   Schatz said he was concerned that the case ``opens the door to a
variety of spurious lawsuits'' by angry lovers.
   Dr. Neil Schram, a member of the California Medical Association's
AIDS task force, called the award ``clearly excessive'' since
Christian apparently wasn't infected, and put the blame for Hudson's
actions on society.
   ``Rock Hudson was required all his life to be sexually dishonest
in order to be successful,'' Schatz said. ``He had to remain in the
closet. As long as society continues to tell people to hate
themselves for their sexuality, then it's hard to expect them to
respect their sexual partners and be honest.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
