<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--SpruanceRepairs     02-17 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Spruance Repairs,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Says Repairs To Cost $1 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAYPORT NAVAL STATION, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy will pay $1 million
to repair the USS Spruance, a destroyer that ran aground on a coral
reef in the Bahamas last month, officials said.
   Repairs began this week at Ingalls Shipbuilding in Pascagoula,
Miss., and should be completed this month, said Ray Sykes, a Navy
spokesman in Pascagoula.
   The ship's propellers and propeller hubs will be repaired, as
well as the mast, which was damaged due to windy weather and high
seas during the grounding, Sykes said.
   The ship ran aground Jan. 25 about three miles east of Andros
Island, the largest island in the Bahamas, during a four-day
training exercise at the Navy's Atlantic Undersea Test and
Evaluation Center.
   The destroyer, based at Mayport, was refloated three days later
and towed to Pascagoula.
   Navy officials have said they will not discuss how the Spruance
was grounded until an investigation is completed. But based on
preliminary findings, Cmdr. Travis W. Parker Jr. was relieved as the
Spruance's commander and reassigned.
</TEXT>
