<DOCNO> AP890217-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-17-89 1542EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon Bjt   02-17 0688</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, Bjt,0710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Militia Chief Withdraws Fighters After Threats From Army Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The commander of Lebanon's main Christian
militia ordered his fighters to withdraw from battle Friday after
the army chief threatened an ``apocalpyse'' to wipe them out.
   Lebanese Forces commander Samir Geagea, who has been fighting for
control of the nation's Christian community, said he was willing to
dissolve the militia if a conference of Christian religious and
political leaders asked him to.
   Intermittent duels with artillery and automatic weapons flared
earlier in the Christian sector of the divided capital, despite a
cease-fire signed Wednesday by Geagea and Gen. Michel Aoun, the army
chief.
   In Washington, Defense Department officials said at least 13
employees of the U.S. Embassy were evacuated to Cyprus. A Defense
Department employee, speaking on condition of anonymity, said about
25 remained at the embassy, which the State Department says has been
caught in a cross fire.
   The battles have deepened divisions in the Christian community in
this nation already torn by 14 years of civil war between Christians
and Moslems.
   In an effort to resolve the inter-Christian conflict peacefully,
Maronite Patriarch Nasrallah Sfeir held a conference attended by 21
leading Maronite leaders in Bkirki, north of Beirut.
   Geagea told reporters after the four-hour meeting: ``I am
ordering all Lebanese Forces militiamen to withdraw from all fronts
back to their barracks. Never again will we collide with the army.''
   ``Whatever the general (Aoun) wants, we'll do,'' Geagea said.
   Asked if he will be willing to dissolve the 6,000-strong Lebanese
Forces, Geagea said, ``If the Bkirki conferees say so, I will. But
they haven't taken such a decision.''
   He said he was prepared to pull his militia from Christian east
Beirut if the Moslem sector was simultaneously brought under
exclusive control of the Lebanese army.
   ``From now on, we and Gen. Aoun are one hand,'' he declared.
   There was no immediate reaction from Aoun, who boycotted the
meeting. A statement by the conferees said they had briefed Aoun on
the deliberations. The conferees resolved to consolidate the
cease-fire, withdraw Lebanese Forces militiamen to their barracks
and apply law and order across Lebanon.
   Aoun, head of the Christian Cabinet in Lebanon's dual
Moslem-Christian government, told a news conference earlier the
conditions that permitted the army to coexist with the militia no
longer existed.
   ``We are responsible for the state, and they want a ministate ...
Those who do not abide by the law, I'll crush their heads,'' said
Aoun, surrounded by senior officers of his 20,000-member
predominantly Christian army.
   Aoun said he had accepted a cease-fire mediated by Sfeir on
Wednesday only to allow political efforts to ``resolve the problem
peacefully.''
   ``Otherwise, it will be total destruction. This time it will be
an apocalypse,'' he said.
   Shortly after the news conference, the army announced that 2nd
Lt. Joseph Bitar was killed by sniper fire from Lebanese Forces
positions in east Beirut. That brought the death toll to 70 in
fighting that broke out late Tuesday. At least 197 people were
wounded.
   Aoun said the Lebanese Forces should compensate the people for
the damage and casualties out of taxes the militia levies.
   He said the militia charges about $400,000 a day in illegal
taxation of various businesses in the 310-square-mile enclave that
houses 1 million Christians.
   The Lebanese Forces and the various Moslem and leftist militias
have been collecting taxes in their respective areas of influence
since the civil war broke out in 1975.
   Aoun accused the militia of starting the previous round of
fighting, which involved an attack on his residence in east Beirut's
posh suburb of Rabieh.
   He said his forces ``confronted the attack,'' capturing five
armored personnel carriers and their crews.
   Aoun was named head of an interim military Cabinet by former
President Amin Gemayel minutes before Gemayel's term expired Sept.
22. Parliament has failed to elect a successor because Christians
opposed the Syrian-backed candidates.
   Aoun's appointment violated an unwritten national covenant that
gave the premiership to the Sunni Moslems, the presidency to the
Maronites and the house speakership to the Shiite Moslems.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
