<DOCNO> AP890217-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-17-89 1548EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0613 02-17 0886</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0613,830</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 5 grafs new material</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush, Congressional Leaders Set Face-to-Face Budget Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Friday that fledgling talks
with Congress on his $1.16 trillion spending plan are making
progress and he will sit down with House and Senate leaders next
week to push for ``a quick and early resolution to this budget
crisis.''
   The president said top Democrats and Republicans in Congress will
come to the White House on Tuesday, the eve of Bush's departure on a
five-day trip to Asia.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said the session was
intended to keep the momentum of budget talks going while Bush was
out of the country.
   Bush announced the conference with congressional leaders during a
speech before students at Washington University, his third address
in a week on the budget.
   He got a warm reception in the university field house, though
outside his motorcade encountered handfuls of demonstrators against
his anti-abortion stance.
   In his speech, Bush once again failed to offer a formula to
produce the $9.6 billion to $11 billion in budget cuts needed to
offset the cost of his commitments for new spending on domestic
programs such as education, child care, the homeless and cleaning up
the environment.
   ``There are certain priorities that demand attention,'' Bush
said. ``Yes, we can afford to increase spending _ modestly,
selectively but only after tough choices are made.''
   Democrats have complained that the president is taking credit for
expanding social spending while making Congress take responsibility
for finding ways to pay for it.
   However, Bush gave an upbeat assessment of the budget talks,
which are in their infancy, saying ``We are making progress.''
Suggesting he would share responsibility with Congress, he said,
``Together, we've got to make the budget process work.''
   ``I am committed to working closely with my friends on the Hill
to help them meet the target date set by the Gramm-Rudman-Hollings
law for an April 15th budget resolution,'' Bush said.
   That law, which requires a balanced budget by 1993, calls for a
deficit in the fiscal year that begins next Oct. 1 of no more than
$100 billion _ down from an estimated $160 billion this year.
   Failure by Congress to meet the target could result in
across-the-board cuts.
   Bush said he wanted congressional leaders ``to come meet with me
and in a spirit of bipartisanship get on with the nation's business
of getting a quick and early resolution to this budget crisis.''
   In his remarks, Bush also stressed volunteerism _ one of his
favorite themes.
   ``My friends, from now on in America any definition of a
successful life must include serving others, in child-care center,
in the corporate boardroom, at the Rotary, at Little League, or a
tutoring program, and in a church or synagogue,'' Bush said.
   As for a federal role, he said, ``I know we can have a government
with a heart as well as a head.''
   Bush struck a decidely different tone from his predecessor,
Ronald Reagan, who portrayed the government almost as an enemy.
   ``The government's contribution is critical but by itself is
insufficient to solve all of our national problems,'' Bush said.
   ``Yes, most Americans believe that our efforts must reach beyond
government, to care about our communities and to assist our
neighbors,'' the president said. ``But they also believe that
government can be an important catalyst in that process of helping
individuals, our communities and our nation.''
   Fitzwater said participants at Tuesday's budget meeting will
include House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas; Majority Leader Tom
Foley, D-Wash.; Minority Leader Bob Michel, R-Ill.; Senate Majority
Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine; Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole,
R-Kan., and the senior Democrats and Republicans from the
congressional budget, finance and appropriations committees.
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady, budget chief Richard Darman
and White House chief of staff John Sununu also will take part.
   After the speech, Bush had lunch with about two dozen people,
including students, senior citizens and participants in the Special
Olympics programs.
   The president would not respond to questions by reporters on a
soon-to-be-released FBI report on the qualifications of former Sen.
John Tower to be defense secretary. ``We're not going to have any
press questions. I'm not worried. I feel good today,'' Bush said.
   In Washington, congressional sources who requested anonymity said
a review of a security clearance application by a retired Air Force
officer included allegations about Tower's behavior as the head of
an American delegation to arms talks in Geneva in 1985 and 1986.
Among the allegations was one that Tower kept both his secretaries
in Geneva as mistresses.
   On another subject, Fitzwater told reporters that while Bush was
in St. Louis a letter to the president, delivered by Soviet
Ambassador Yuri Dubinin, had arrived at the White House from Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Fitzwater said that Bush had not had the opportunity to read the
letter in full and that a response had not been prepared. The
spokesman said Gorbachev's message ``relates generally to the
pullout of Soviet forces in Afghanistan. It generally repeats their
public position.''
   In Moscow, officials said Gorbachev had sent messages to Bush and
other world leaders asking for help in ending the war between Afghan
factions following the Red Army pullout.
</TEXT>
