<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv21   02-17 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 21,0665</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv21</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Tues, Feb 21</HEAD>
<HEAD>Is The Quality of Service Improving?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the most cynical little intrusions into
the quality of life today is the telephone solicitation at
dinnertime from a bank promoting a credit card or a marketing firm
conducting a survey.
   Most people would probably rank it as one of those nagging little
mosquuito bites of life that must be endured, too small a matter to
make an issue of, but certainly an irritant that their lives could
do without.
   It is when the mosquitoes swarm that the minor peeves become
unendurable, and no less an authority on the subject than ``The
Quality Review'' has given recognition to the disturbing phenomenon.
   The review, published by the American Quality Foundation and the
American Society for Quality Control, usually concerns itself with
momentous issues of product quality, especially as they relate to
American competitiveness.
   In the past, for example, it has declaimed on such matters as
Detroit's manufacturing problems, Japan's production efficiencies,
and engineering and statistical strategies for maintaining high
quality in goods production.
   Its descent into the more mundane world of pet peeves is provoked
by the feeling that the mosquitoes are everywhere, and that all
those little bites are leaving a welt on the quality of life equal
to that of shoddy products.
   Judging from its list, the irritants are all the more irritating
because as the country immerses itself deeper into the service
economy _ as opposed to an economy of goods production _ it may be
getting less service than ever before.
   First on its list is the unreturned telephone call. Making it
especially frustrating is that the original call probably was
received by a machine which, in its recorded voice, assured the
caller that a response would be forthcoming.
   It may lead to telephone tag, with each party making successive
fruitless attempts to return a call. The Review editors comment that
``this time-wasting endeavor is equivalent to rework in the
manufacturing arena.''
   Dinnertime sales or solicitation calls earned second place on the
list, and provoked the suggestion that the way to deal with them is
to screen your calls through an answering machine. Which, however,
may be your friends' pet peeve.
   Hotel telephone operators who leave you holding the phone so long
that you have to redial _ long-distance _ in order to leave a
message, make the list.
   ``Indefinitely delayed'' notices at airports earn a place, along
with the comment, ``If the airline can't bring itself to be upfront
with the information that this flight may never leave the ground,
maybe they could post the odds.''
   Travelers who pre-empt overhead baggage compartments, sales
clerks who turn their backs on customers to serve telephone
customers instead, and servicemen or delivery men who keep you
waiting all day are high on the Review's list.
   One of the more serious of its pet peeves _ one that seemingly
could rank with some of the old-fashioned complaints that quality
control people used to be concerned with _ is the service contract.
   Even customers who purchase these contracts think they are a bad
idea, it says. It asks: ``Why should anyone need a five-year service
contract on a water heater that is `guaranteed' for 10 years?''
   All pet peeve lists are likely to differ, especially if an
attempt is made to limit them to a specific number.
   The Review, for example, feels that impenetrable packaging,
ranging from cracker wrappings to appliance containers, and
including envelopes that require tools to open, belong on many
lists, if not theirs.
   But it suggests that the diversity of lists merely proves the
point that there are so many of these little irritants swarming
through our service society that they are serving to create a major
problem.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Tues, Feb 21</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890217-0146 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-17-89 0659EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a w AM-MurderCapital Adv20 2Takes 02-17 0841</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Murder Capital, Adv 20, 2 Takes,0864</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday AMs, Feb. 20, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Welcome to Washington, Murder Capital of the USA</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's the capital of the free world and the
murder capital of the United States.
   Just one night last week, three people were killed in the
District of Columbia. Typically, all were shootings and all, police
said, could be drug-related.
   By Wednesday, 75 people had been killed this year in Washington,
compared with 46 by the same time in 1988. Last year set a city
record with 372 homicides _ virtually one a day and 145 more than in
1987.
   At the current rate, the city could log more than 600 murders
this year.
   The pace of the killings in 1988 _ 59.4 for each 100,000
residents _ gave Washington a distinction it didn't want: Murder
Capital USA. Detroit, which held the title in 1987, had 58 murders
per 100,000 residents.
   Why Washington?
   Police officers and experts agree: handguns and a sudden influx
of cheap drugs.
   Both are easy to come by and both are increasingly finding their
way into the hands of young Washingtonians, many of whom have become
armed delivery people caught in wars between drug gangs.
   Ten of the 42 people killed in October were teen-agers. Seven
more were in their early 20s.
   It wasn't always so.
   ``Washington didn't become a target for the drug trade as early
as other large cities did,'' said Gwynne Peirson, a retired
criminology professor at Howard University who spent 23 years as a
police officer in Oakland, Calif. ``It's a relatively recent
phenomenon here because the population of Washington isn't the size
of many other cities, so it wasn't as attractive a market
initially.''
   That changed with the coming of crack, a highly potent and
addictive _ but cheap to get hooked on _ form of cocaine that can be
smoked.
   A typical dose of 100 milligrams, which a regular user might
smoke a dozen or more times a day, sells on the street for about
$10, said Maurice Hill of the Drug Enforcement Administration. A
75-milligram ``starter'' dose often goes for $5.
   ``The average kid with an allowance can buy crack unimpeded,''
said Mario Perez, a DEA agent. ``All he has to do is shake hands
with his best buddy outside the school house.''
   One expert said the very nature of crack has driven up the murder
rate.
   ``There's something about the nature of crack that makes people
crazy, makes them impulsive and likely to do irrational things,''
said Hubert Williams of the Police Foundation, a research
organization.
   ``I've heard crack addicts say use of crack opens up every
pleasure center in the body,'' said Williams, who was a police
officer for 24 years in Newark, N.J. ``The sensations are so high
and also so short in terms of duration that almost after taking the
first one, you need a second one because you're on a downer. So you
have an ideal set of circumstances to create a huge market.''
   Then there is the presence of guns.
   Ten to 20 years ago, high school students might have carried pen
knives as protection. Today, said a city officer who requested
anonymity, the protection is a handgun, often an automatic.
   ``We have people who are settling their arguments with guns,'' he
said.
   Of the almost 1,600 weapons seized by police since late 1986
through Operation Clean Sweep, an undercover operation aimed at drug
dealers, more than 1,200 have been handguns.
   To all that, add the high unemployment rate among the city's
black teens. In 1987, the last full year for which statistics are
available, 22.4 percent had looked for legitimate work, but failed.
   ``It's an easy market with so many poor, unskilled black people
willing to take the small risk,'' Peirson said. ``With people that
are uneducated and unskilled, the idea of standing out on a street
making $500 to $1,000 a night with the chances of getting caught
relatively small, it's a small risk.''
   Teen-agers and even younger children are being recruited to man
the front lines on the drug battleground ``because the
narco-traffickers know full well that we live in a society that
treats children as children,'' Perez said. ``They shield themselves
by the children, who become targets of opportunity for other
competitors. ... Most of the people being killed have barely begun
to shave.''
   Often these couriers work for one of the rival gangs of black
Americans, Jamaicans, Nigerians and Latins battling for the same
turf, said Perez.
   ``If there was something organized, maybe the (number of
homicides) would be placated somewhat,'' he said.
   ``These are people who collect their bills one way or the
other,'' Perez added. ``They are very unforgiving for the slightest
error or what seems to be betrayal. ...
   ``These people are presently jockeying for position, establishing
areas of control, fighting for turf. They're very very violent. Get
off my sand dune and stay off my sand dune.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MORE</HEAD>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890217-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-17-89 0702EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a w AM-MurderCapital Adv20 1stAdd 02-17 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Murder Capital, Adv 20, 1st Add,0647</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release AMs Mon Feb. 20 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>WASHN: sand dune.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   What to do about the spiraling murder rate _ and the root
problems of drugs and guns among the city's young _ has so far
eluded officials.
   Operation Clean Sweep has resulted in close to 44,000 arrests,
but one officer said, ``We're arresting the same people, over and
over.'' Besides the arrests, officials say, the undercover effort
has netted 458 seized vehicles, $2.15 million in cash and drugs with
a street value of $16.7 million.
   Mayor Marion S. Barry Jr. cited budget problems when the program
was reduced in November, but some police union officials say the
effort has virtually ceased in the worst crime areas.
   Peirson contends merely arresting and sentencing street dealers
won't do much good.
   ``They can do prison standing on their heads,'' he said,
remembering a conversation with a prison warden in Morgantown, W.Va.
   ``She pointed out that 90 percent of them (the inmates) when they
arrived had never seen a dentist, had never seen an eye doctor. Now
they had doctors, three meals a day, as much as they wanted. This is
not the kind of punishment that's going to deter them.''
   The mayor, himself involved in a federal investigation of his
personal and professional life, said after last week's three-murder
night that ``the only thing I can do is give people hope that I'm
doing what I can. (The people) want ideas. They want programs. They
want action.''
   Yet, his proposed budget would give the Police Department just 5
percent more in 1990.
   Rather than more money, Barry thinks the department can do better
with what it has.
   ``In the short run,'' said mayoral spokesman John White, ``he has
asked the Police Department to study the way in which it has
assigned its manpower so that more police officers will be on the
street rather than inside on administrative duties. The mayor
believes the size of the police force is sufficient, but there needs
to be better allocation of resources than we have.''
   Not everyone on the city council agrees with Barry's approach.
   ``People are outraged,'' said Councilwoman Nadine Winter. ``I'm
telling him he doesn't have it under control. He ought to call for
help.''
   Winter would have President Bush declare a state of emergency and
``deploy every available resource,'' even the National Guard, as
part of the battle.
   For its part, the White House, through press secretary Marlin
Fitzwater, said last week that ``everyone in the country, including
the president, is outraged by the homicides whether it be in
Washington, D.C., or California or anywhere else.''
   ``There are any number of appropriate solutions to this kind of
problem,'' Fitzwater said. ``The most obvious is for stepped-up law
enforcement.''
   Most of the drug-related shootings have been in the Southeast and
Northeast quadrants of the city, where a majority of its poor, black
residents live. But some have spilled over into largely affluent
Northwest Washington.
   Less than 1{ miles from the White House, drug dealers peddle
their wares along a corridor from 13th to 16th streets, NW.
   Diplomats at the Spanish Embassy on 15th Street, NW, are wary of
their neighborhood.
   ``This area ... is well known for being a center strongly related
to drugs and violence,'' said embassy spokeswoman Helga Soto.
``Consequently, the members of our embassy do not feel secure at all
when entering or leaving the premises.''
   So far, the violence hasn't dissuaded tourists, who average about
19 million a year, from coming to town, said Austin Kenny, executive
vice president of the Washington Area Convention and Visitors Bureau.
   ``The only people asking questions (about violence in the city)
are reporters,'' Kenny said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for AMs Mon Feb. 20 and thereafter</NOTE>
</DOC>
