<FILEID>AP-NR-02-17-89 1318EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-Recycling-States Adv26   02-17 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Recycling-States, Adv 26 ,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Feb. 26, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ten States Mandate Recycling</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Recycling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a look at laws in the 10 states and the District of
Columbia that have laws requiring some form of recycling:
   _RHODE ISLAND: Residents must separate newspapers and rinsed cans
and bottles into containers for pickup.
   _NEW JERSEY: Residents must separate recyclable materials.
Municipalities have until end of 1989 to recycle 25 percent of
garbage.
   _PENNSYLVANIA: Residents must separate recyclables. Goal is 25
percent recycling by 1997.
   _OREGON: Municipalities with populations over 4,000 must provide
drop-off centers and make curbside collection of recyclables at
least once a month.
   _DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA: Offices must recycle paper and newspaper
and residents must recycle newspaper and yard waste by Oct. 1.
Residents and businesses will have to separate metals and glass by
the end of 1990.
   _CONNECTICUT: Recyclable materials are banned from landfills.
State is setting up six recycling centers.
   _FLORIDA: Counties must have recycling programs in place by July.
Plastic food-packaging materials are banned unless they degrade
within specified times. Goal is 30 percent recycling.
   _MARYLAND: Counties have been ordered to create recycling plans.
Goal is 20 percent recycling for counties with more than 150,000
people.
   _HAWAII: Residents must be given the opportunity to recycle, with
collection centers and monthly curbside pickup in urban areas. But
law says recyclable materials cannot cost more to collect and sell
than to collect and dispose of.
   _ILLINOIS: Chicago and large counties are required to develop
comprehensive waste management plans emphasizing recycling and
landfilling within two years. Goal is 25 percent recycling in seven
years.
   _NEW YORK: Municipalities have until Sept 1., 1992, to establish
programs requiring residents to separate recyclable materials that
do not cost more to collect and sell than to collect and dispose.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Feb. 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
