<DOCNO> AP890217-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-17-89 1417EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-CocaineTown Adv26-1stadd   02-17 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Cocaine Town, Adv 26-1st add,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Feb. 26, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>TOCACHE: cocaine trade.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   School Superintendent William Tirado says bitterly the town's
teachers have become steadily poorer, while uneducated peasants from
the Andes have grown wealthy overnight.
   ``They arrived poor and have become rich while we, the teachers,
the ones with education, are poorer than ever,'' Tirado says. ``The
only ones who have failed to progress are those who have not
participated in this illicit business.''
   Police say most of Tocache's residents, including prosperous
merchants and bar keepers, continue cultivating coca outside of town
even after they make enough money to open legitimate businesses.
   Townspeople are suspicious of outsiders and most refuse to
acknowledge their direct involvement in the illegal, often deadly
enterprise of cocaine trafficking.
   Pascual Mendieta, 30, the owner of the electronics store, says he
stopped growing coca since opening his business.
   ``I planted a little coca and after two years I had enough money
to open this store,'' he said. ``Business has gone well. I have no
complaints.''
   Daniel Aguilar, the shoeshing boy, was in Tocache 12 hours after
his mother put him on a bus in the mountain town of Huanuco and not
long after that he was earning five dollars a day _ three times the
national minimum wage.
   ``I send money home to my mother each week so my brothers and
sisters can eat,'' he says proudly.
   Tocache's growth was made possible by the Jungle Highway, a
visionary project launched 25 years ago during the administration of
President Fernando Belaunde Terry to spur colonization of Peru's
virtually uninhabited tropical forests. The highway, running 1,000
miles north to south, hugs the lower eastern slopes of the Andes.
   ``The coca boom began when the jungle was opened up,'' says Edgar
Machado, a professor at the National Agrarian University in Lima and
an expert on coca. ``That was when the migration of landless
campesinos began. They were the pioneers of the jungle and the first
thing they did was plant coca as the most profitable crop
available.''
   Miguel Gonzalez, 33, manager of a small restaurant and one of the
few born here, recalls that when he was a boy, Tocache was a sleepy
village of several hundred farmers.
   ``People used coca to chew. They knew nothing about cocaine,'' he
says, referring to the centuries-old Andean tradition of chewing
coca leaves to dampen hunger and increase energy.
   Things began to change when drug-trafficking gangs, under
pressure from police, moved their base of operations to Tocache from
Aucayacu and Tingo Maria, the valley's biggest town, 80 miles south
of here.
   ``Since 1984 drug traffickers have been considered the upper
crust of Tocache society,'' School Superintendnent Tirado says with
an ironic chuckle. ``Moral values have been turned upside down.
Young people have lost all interest in studying. They want money,
and the quickest way to get money is to plant coca.''
   The biggest drug trafficker of all was ``The Vampire.'' He is
believed to still be in the area although he has not returned to
town.
   People say his name was fitting: He lived in a sprawling,
garishly decorated home with a blood-red ceiling and similarly
colored furniture. When he saw an attractive woman on the street, he
took her and if her companion was foolish enough to protest, he
killed him.
   The Vampire's favorite killing spot was the bridge over the
Huallaga River. Backed up by his henchmen, he would take his victims
there, drive a knife into their chests or shoot them through the
head and dump their bodies into the swift-flowing river, townspeople
say.
   ``I knew The Vampire,'' says Daniel, the shoeshine boy. ``He
lived in the `casa grande.' I shined his shoes. He gave me big tips
and joked with me. But when he was in a bad mood, he was mean.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Feb. 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
