<FIRST>r f PM-Bush-Trip Bjt   02-17 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Trip, Bjt,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says He Will Work for Budget Cuts, Too</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Speech begins about 11:30 a.m. EST; Tops expected. This also
moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is disputing criticism that his
$1.16 trillion budget allows him to take credit for proposing
expanded social spending while sticking Congress with finding ways
to pay for it.
   ``It's a two-way street,'' Bush said as he vowed to make good on
his commitment to work with Congress on spending cuts.
   The president, who made the remarks on Thursday in an Oval Office
interview with a group of reporters, was to give yet another
out-of-town speech today promoting that fiscal 1990 spending plan.
   His talk at Washington University in St. Louis was his third
speech on the budget since he unveiled it a week ago before a joint
session of Congress. Bush made similar remarks to business leaders
in New Hampshire on Monday and to state legislators in South
Carolina on Wednesday.
   Today's address also was expected to stress volunteerism in the
private sector _ one of Bush's pet themes.
   Democratic critics have called Bush's budget vague on where he
would make between $9.6 billion and $11 billion in cuts to carry out
his commitments for new spending on domestic programs like
education, child care, the homeless and cleaning up the environment.
   ``I said ahead of time I didn't expect everybody would jump up
and down and say this is the greatest thing since sliced bread,''
Bush said on Thursday.
   But he rejected the notion that he had been deliberately vague in
the budget to put the onus on Congress alone for coming up with
unpopular spending cuts.
   ``Yes, there's a lot more detail that has to be hammered out. And
we will work with them to satisfy their interests, and find out what
they want. It's a two way street,'' Bush said.
   He said he was generally pleased with the reaction so far toward
both his budget plan and to his program to rescue the nation's
ailing savings and loans _ even though he conceded that the twin
plans weren't universally popular.
   Bush also denied anew any major policy rift with Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan, even though they hold different views on
inflation and interest rates.
   ``It's one of the best fights in town,'' Bush said of battles
between a president and a Fed chief. ``You all love it, all
politicians love it, bankers like it, all editorialists for the Wall
Street Journal love it. But I want to avoid that because we aren't
far apart.''
   Greenspan's Fed has been nudging up short-term rates in recent
months in an effort to minimize inflation risks. Bush said Thursday:
``I don't see the inflationary pressures as so bad, or enough, to
warrant substantially higher interest rates.''
   Higher interest rates could the dampen economic growth that Bush
is counting on to produce government revenue gains assumed in his
budget.
</TEXT>
