<DOCNO> AP890217-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-17-89 0837EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Inflation     02-17 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Inflation,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Annual Rate Jumps To 7.5 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's annual inflation rate surged to 7.5
percent in January from 6.8 percent in the previous month, pushed to
its highest level in more than six years by higher mortgage rates,
the government said Friday.
   The Department of Employment said its retail price index rose 0.6
percent in January from the previous month.
   The index, which uses a 1987 base of 100, stood at 111 in
January, crease of 7.3 percent to 7.5 percent. Chancellor of the
Exchequer Nigel Lawson warned last Saturday that the rise was likely
to be much above the 6.8 percent increase recorded for December.
   The 7.5 percent inflation rate is the highest since mid-1982.
   Share prices retreated on London's Stock Exchange on the news,
and the pound rose a bit. Trading in the markets was quiet.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was down 14.4
points, or 0.7 percent, at 2,019.4 after the report was released.
The index was 12.5 points lower before.
   The pound was quoted at $1.7785 vs. $1.7780 earlier.
   ``These figures do show very strong inflationary pressures,''
said Nigel Richardson, an analyst with the London investment firm
Rowe and Pitman, Mullins and Co.
   The department said the rise was mainly due to higher mortgage
interest payments, reflecting mortgage rate hikes made in January
following the late-November rise in the British commercial banks'
base rate to 13 percent from 12 percent.
   Excluding mortgage payments, the department said the annual
inflation rate was 5.5 percent.
   The government remains determined to bring inflation down, but
one consequence of using the higher interest rates as its weapon is
higher inflation in the short-term, the department said.
   The January increase also reflected higher food prices, motor
insurance premiums and rail fares, it said.
</TEXT>
