<FILEID>AP-NR-02-17-89 0923EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-SteelImports     02-17 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steel Imports,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Importer Disputes Domestic Producers' Steel Supply Claims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite claims by domestic producers of excess
steel production capacity worldwide, a leading importer says there
are shortages that justify a second look at U.S. steel trade quotas.
   U.S. steelmakers, demanding another five years of quotas, cite
excess world capacity of 100 million tons or more per year of steel
as the basis for cutthroat trading practices.
   ``I assure you most steel is imported into this market because it
fills specific needs of American steel users,'' said Erwin L. Klein,
a director and immediate past president of the American Institute
for Imported Steel.
   ``That may help dispel the notion most steel brought into this
country is foisted on American buyers by means of unfair trade
practices.''
   References to foreign production overcapacity as a cause of
problems for the U.S. steel industry may concern obsolete plants and
marginal product categories, Klein said in a speech prepared for
delivery Thursday night in Hasbrouck Heights, N.J., to the
Association of Women in the Metals Industries.
   ``Though global surplus is widely discussed, we have all
encountered specific product shortages in the past year,'' said
Klein, who is also vice chairman of Steelinter USA Inc. of New York,
a major importer of Belgian steel.
   The shortages involve plate, large structural shapes and rod, he
said.
   The New York-based importers association says the Bush
administration should ease the steel import restrictions under the
five-year quota plan due to expire in September. Bush has promised
American producers to extend the protection.
   U.S. producers say another five years of quotas are necessary if
they are to fully recover from a near disasterous slump in their
industry from 1982-86. They accuse foreign steel producers,
especially those in Europe, of producing excess steel with
government subsidies to maintain employment in their countries.
   Klein said that since the early 1970s domestic steel buyers had
been forced to turn to foreign suppliers not only for particular
types of steel but also because total domestic steelmaking capacity
repeatedly had fallen short of demand.
   The shortfall was more than 20 million tons in 1988, and ``the
problem was especially acute in the West and Southwest, where
domestic production facilities were insufficient,'' he said.
   Importers have asked that Bush make any further quotas temporary
with a timetable for being phased out. They want quotas to be
voluntary and constantly adjusted to suit the needs of steel users.
   The importers also say semifinished steel products imported by
American producers should not be covered by the quota plan.
   The interests of steel-consuming manufacturers should get equal
consideration with those of the large steel producers, Klein said.
   Those steel-users ``create 25 times more value, employ 30 times
more workers and export nearly 100 times more in dollar terms than
the steel industry,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
