<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0016,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises in Europe After U.S. Trade Report</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To UPDATE with dollar rising on U.S. trade figures, Top 9 grafs
new. Picks up 12th graf pvs, Gold opened...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against major foreign currencies in
Europe today after the U.S. government reported the country's trade
deficit narrowed in December.
   The U.S. Commerce Department said the December trade deficit
declined to $11.9 billion from a revised November figure of $12.2
billion. The November shortfall was originally reported at $12.5
billion.
   One Milan trader had said that there would be a greater tendency
to sell than buy the dollar should a neutral figure emerge from the
Washington report.
   This trader defined a neutral result as somewhere between $11
billion and $12 billion.
   Milan traders said there were far fewer ``dollar bulls'' in the
market than at the same time last week, due largely to mounting
opinion that the U.S. Federal Reserve was not about to hike U.S
interest rates, as many had been expecting.
   In London, the dollar improved against the British pound after
the trade report. It cost $1.7720 to buy one pound compared with
$1.7770 at midmorning and $1.7712 Thursday.
   Other dollar rates after the report was released with midmorning
rates in parentheses and compared with late Thursday's levels
included: 1.8440 (1.8350) West German marks, up from 1.8425; 1.5650
(1.5590) Swiss francs, up from 1.5643; 6.2685 (6.2500) French
francs, down from 6.2725; 2.0760 (2.0725) Dutch guilders, down from
2.0790; 1,344.00 (1,343.50) Italian lire, down from 1,348.50; and,
1.1918 (1.1875) Canadian dollars, up from 1.1859.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.61 yen to a closing 125.72. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 126 yen after the report and 125.75 yen before.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $378 a troy ounce, down
from $382.25 bid late Thursday. At midmorning today, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $378.95.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $379, down from $382.50 bid late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $5.02 to close at a bid $380.18.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $5.80 a troy
ounce, down from Thursday's $5.84.
</TEXT>
