<HEAD>Teamsters Promise To Back Machinists In Event Of Eastern Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of Atlanta's largest Teamsters local says
his union will honor machinists union pickets at Hartsfield Atlanta
International Airport in case of a strike against Eastern Airlines.
   The strike could come March 3 unless talks that started 16 months
ago end in a settlement.
   Teamsters represent truckers at several major companies doing
business at the nation's second-busiest airport, including United
Parcel Service.
   Machinists President Michael J. Flynn said that Lamar Mathis,
trustee of Teamsters Local 928, has vowed ``a Teamster truck will
not cross our picket lines.''
   The impact of Machinist pickets would depend on whether courts
allow them to picket entire airports or limit them to Eastern
facilities. Teamsters represent a variety of employees at other
airlines, including drivers of airline fuel trucks.
   Eastern is seeking $150 million in concessions over each of the
next three years. The machinists have proposed a one-year wage
freeze and raises totaling 8 percent over the next two years.
   Federal mediators plan to convene negotiators for both sides in
Washington next week to try to avoid a walkout.
