<FIRST>r f PM-Envirodyne     02-17 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Envirodyne,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kelly, Back In Takeover Game, Bids For Envirodyne</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock price of Envirodyne Industries Inc., a
Chicago manufacturer of sausage casings and plastics, has soared
following a takeover bid by former Beatrice boss Donald P. Kelly.
   Envirodyne jumped $4.50 a share to $37.25 Thursday in
over-the-counter trading on news of Kelly's $690 million offer.
   Envirodyne of Chicago said it had discussions with Kelly and
investment banker Salomon Brothers Inc. on their proposal to acquire
all of the company's outstanding stock for $38 a share.
   With 18.2 million shares outstanding, the offer values Envirodyne
at $690 million.
   Envirodyne spokeswoman Helen Gallagher said company executives
had not decided whether a sale would be in the best interests of
shareholders.
   Kelly, the former chairman of Beatrice Co., declined to comment
on the offer.
   He heads D.P. Kelly &amp; Associates, a Chicago firm he formed after
resigning from Beatrice last year to seek, in partnership with
Salomon, acquisitions of ``undervalued companies.''
   Envirodyne also said it had been asked by Artra Group Inc., which
owns 26.3 percent of Envirodyne, to consider Artra's participation
with Kelly and Salomon.
   Last August, Artra tried and failed to put together a cash offer
for Envirodyne that would have been worth about $36 per share.
   Artra officials declined to comment. The company, based in
Northfield, owns Sargent-Welch Scientific Co. and 70 percent of Lori
Corp., a jewelry and accessories business.
   Kelly, 66, rose to prominence in the 1970s by transforming
meatpacker Swift &amp; Co. into Esmark Inc., a conglomerate of food and
consumer products. He sold Esmark to Beatrice in 1984, then teamed
up two years later with leveraged buyout specialist Kohlberg, Kravis
Roberts &amp; Co. to purchase Beatrice for $6.2 billion.
   Kelly announced his resignation from Beatrice in August after
selling off portions of the company.
</TEXT>
