<FIRST>r f BC-Carl'sExecutive     02-17 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Carl's Executive,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carl's Jr. Exec Indicted For Securities Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Carl's Jr. fast food chain's general
accounting director has been indicted by a federal grand jury on one
count of securities fraud in connection with insider trading.
   Alvin A. DeShano, 53, of Orange, was charged Thursday with
receiving and using confidential company information to avoid a
$7,107 loss on stock involving the Anaheim-based Carl Karcher
Enterprises, which runs the Carl's Jr. hamburger restaurants.
   A statement from Loren Pannier, chief financial officer of
Karcher Enterprises, said, ``Al remains an active employee of the
company. This matter should have no effect on the company's
business.''
   The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission filed a civil lawsuit
last April accusing DeShano of using an Oct. 12, 1984, financial
report to get rid of 1,725 shares of Karcher stock. DeShano sold the
shares on Oct. 15, 1984. On Oct. 23, 1984, Karcher Enterprises
publicly announced that lower earnings resulted in a drop in stock
value.
   DeShano could not immediately be reached for comment Friday. A
call placed to his office before business hours went unanswered.
   His attorney, David M. Wiechert of Irvine, said his client
``never would have intended to deceive or defraud anyone.''
   ``He had legitimate reasons for diversifying his investments and
assets at the time of the sale that were wholly unrelated to the
information,'' Wiechert said.
   The SEC lawsuit also accused Karcher Enterprises Chairman and
Chief Executive Officer Carl N. Karcher along with 14 of his
relatives of avoiding more than $300,000 in stock losses. Six of the
16 defendants, including company President Donald F. Karcher, have
agreed to pay $187,560 in fines and penalties to end their
involvement in the SEC suit.
   The remaining defendants, including DeShano, are scheduled to
stand trial on April 11. DeShano is the only one who has been
criminally charged.
   If convicted he could be sentenced to up to five years in prison
and fined $250,000.
</TEXT>
