<FIRST>r f BC-SovietTrade     02-17 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Soviet Trade,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: U.S.-Soviet Trade Proposal Would Allow Repatriation Of Dollars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of U.S. companies is close to completing
a proposed trade pact with the Soviet Union that would allow foreign
businesses for the first time to take profits out of that country in
dollars, according to a published report.
   Executives of the six U.S. companies, called the American Trade
Consortium, and officials of more than 30 Soviet trade and economic
organizations have negotiated for nine months to complete the
agreement, Business Week said in its Feb. 27 issue.
   The accord, which was expected to be signed by early April, would
clear the way for the six corporations to negotiate joint ventures
in the Soviet Union, and could prove to be the biggest and most
complex trade agreement ever developed between the West and the
Soviets, the magazine said.
   Central to the accord is the guarantee that the countries would
be allowed to repatriate their profits in dollars from the Soviet
Union.
   A number of Western companies already have embarked on joint
ventures in the Soviet Union, but the inability to repatriate
profits in dollars has been seen as a key obstacle in expanding that
field.
   The American Trade Consortium companies include Ford Motor Co.,
RJR Nabisco Co., Chevron Corp., Eastman Kodak Co., Johnson &amp;
Johnson, Archer Daniels Midland Co. and the New York merchant bank
Mercator.
   Foreign companies generally cannot take dollars from the Soviet
Union because the country badly needs the currency to buy imports.
Soviet exports are limited, so dollars are in short supply.
   Under the agreement, the companies earning dollars would create a
cash pool and would be allowed to take dollars out in proportion to
the amount of rubles they put in.
   Chevron would be a key cash provider at the outset, under the
plan, through a joint venture for the export of Soviet oil. While
the other U.S. business would be mainly selling to the Soviet market
for rubles, Chevron would be bringing in dollars. Chevron's earnings
would then go into the cash pool to cover any profits that are
repatriated by the companies.
   The hard currency U.S. companies need to repatriate their profits
will be guaranteed by Soviet institutions.
   The other U.S. companies also are working out their own deals.
   Eastman Kodak has been negotiating to produce blood analyzers and
floppy disks as well as to sell film and operate photofinishing
laboratories; Archer Daniels Midland is negotiating to set up a
factory to produce fructose, starch and ethanol; Johnson &amp; Johnson
is looking to health products ventures; and RJR Nabisco is
negotiating the manufacture of cereals, crackers and cigarettes, the
magazine stated.
   Ford is working on a venture to help the Soviets revitalize their
auto industry starting with the import into the USSR of its Scorpio
model and eventually setting up production facilities.
   Last month, the American Trade Consortium offered to buy the
partially built U.S. Embassy in Moscow for use as business offices
for the group.
   The United States halted construction on the embassy because it
was found to have been riddled with Soviet listening devices while
the Soviets were building it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
