<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Slip In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mostly lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade in a continuation of the selling
that brought soybean and wheat prices down sharply near the close of
Thursday's session.
   Major factors in the sell-off include improved growing conditions
in South America and reports that France has overcome some
logistical hurdles to completing a sale of 1.5 million metric tons
of wheat to the Soviet Union.
   The development lessens the possibility that the Soviets will
need to increase their purchases of U.S. wheat, as some traders had
hoped.
   The Brazilian government on Wednesday issued a report pegging the
1988-89 Brazilian soybean crop at 22.6 million metric tons, an
increase from the 21.5 million to 22.1 million metric tons forecast
in December.
   The improved outlook for the South American soybean crop is based
on wetter weather in Brazil and Argentina, where drought conditions
prevailed earlier in the growing season.
   In early trading, wheat was \ cent to 1 cent lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.22 a bushel; corn was 1 cent to
1{ cents lower with March at $2.67} a bushel; oats were 1\ cents
lower to \ cent higher with March at $2.03 a bushel; soybeans were
1} cents to 3\ cents lower with March at $7.25{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures were higher while pork futures were mixed in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .12 cent to .55 cent higher with April at 76.17
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .23 cent to .58 cent higher with
March at 82.30 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent lower to .25 cent
higher with April at 41.92 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.57 cent lower to .28 cent higher with March at 37.85 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Thursday.
</TEXT>
