<FIRST>u f PM-BigThreeProfits 1stLd-Writethru   02-17 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Big Three Profits, 1st Ld-Writethru,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Three's Record Profits Clouded By Forecasts For Slower Economy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Ford announcement of profit-sharing
checks; picks up 5th graf, New vehicle ....</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Big Three automakers set a record with
combined earnings of $11.21 billion last year, but forecasts of
slower economic growth are casting doubt on whether the bonanza can
continue.
   ``I think we're getting a little closer to saturating the market
in cars, and interest rates will begin to take their toll,'' said
auto analyst David Healy of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York,
who predicts Big Three earnings will fall 10 percent to 15 percent
in 1989.
   The combined earnings of General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and
Chrysler Corp. for 1988 were up 14.5 percent from the previous
combined record of $9.79 billion in 1984.
   Ford told its employees today they would get profit-sharing
checks of about $2,800 apiece next month, lower than last year's
$3,700 because of a decline in U.S. earnings. General Motors is
giving profit-sharing checks of about $254 per employee. Chrysler's
will be about $720.
   Analysts predict the U.S. economy will soften this year, taking
the auto industry with it.
   New vehicle sales for the 1989 model year are forecast to fall
from the 15.6 million cars and light trucks sold for 1988 _ the
third best on record _ to about 15 million.
   Given the economic climate, a decrease in vehicle sales might be
better than an increase ``because the increase would imply an
economic boom, and busts follow booms,'' said Scott Merlis, an auto
analyst with Morgan Stanley &amp; Co.
   And even with lower sales and a 15 percent earnings decline in
1989, Merlis said, Detroit ``would still be at a healthy level from
an earnings point of view.''
   Executives from each of the Big Three said cost-cutting programs
helped boost 1988 earnings. GM said it saved $4.8 billion by
trimming costs.
   But one of the unknowns in the automakers' future earnings
equations is the cost of buying incentives that customers have come
to expect.
   GM spokesman Terry Sullivan said the company spent about $4.2
billion on incentives and discounts on option packages in 1988, 55.6
percent more than in 1987.
   David McCammon, Ford's finance vice president and treasurer, said
the No. 2 automaker spent about $400 million more on incentives in
1988 than the previous year. He declined to disclose specifics, but
estimated that Ford spent about 25 percent less per car on
incentives than GM.
   Chrysler spokesman Tom Houston declined to say how much
incentives cost the No. 3 automaker last year or how it compared
with 1987. In the past, Chrysler has used incentives liberally,
gaining market share by selling more cars while losing profits.
   Besides forecasts of dropping vehicle sales volumes and continued
cost- cutting, some experts fear there could be a recession in the
next few years. But even that, some analysts said, wouldn't be a
disastrous for the automobile industry.
   Merlis said the Big Three could increase earnings by 50 percent
over the next five years on flat or lower sales, through massive
cutbacks.
   ``Recessions have a tendency to create belt-tightening,'' he
said. ``The best is yet to come when it comes to the cost-cutting
potential.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
