<FIRST>u f PM-Eastern-Machinists 1stLd-Writethru f0090 02-17 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Machinists, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0090,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Issues Injunctions Against Eastern, Machinists</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: NEW throughout with more detail; No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MILT SOSIN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With a strike deadline looming, a federal judge
issued injunctions today against both Eastern Airlines and the
Machinists union to resolve an aircraft maintenance dispute that the
carrier says has grounded 17 jetliners.
   Senior U.S. District Judge C. Clyde Atkins ruled the militant
union must work on 12 grounded aircraft and members must work
overtime if required by the carrier ``with no slowdowns and no
sickouts.''
   He also decided that work already begun by outside contractors
hired by Eastern on five aircraft will be allowed to continue, but
Eastern has been barred from farming out any more such work during a
30-day cooling-off period in their stalled talks.
   If no contract agreement is reached by midnight March 3, Eastern
is free to impose its own work rules and the 8,500-hundred member
union representing Eastern machinists, baggage handlers and other
ground crews are free to strike.
   ``We have 17 aircraft on the ground, normally we have zero,''
Eastern attorney David Ross told the judge as the airline fought the
union's motion to keep all maintenance work in house. ``We can't get
these done even if we get back to full production.''
   Ross contended there was too much backlog for the Machinists
alone to handle the work, and outsiders are needed to get all of the
aircraft back in service.
   But George Tucker, attorney for the union, responded: ``It's our
work. We can do it. We will work overtime if required, and there
will be no slowdowns.''
   Ross kept repeating that the Machinists will be pushed to the
limit as new aircraft come in for maintenance, and Tucker repeated
the union's arguments that the work has traditionally been down by
organized labor.
   With the attorneys bickering, Atkins broke in and said, ``I've
made my ruling. There will be no more planes or equipment shipped,
but the work may continue on the five planes that are already
undergoing work.''
   ``I am entering an injunction against both sides effective from
now on until March 3. The company can continue the work on the five
that are already out, but no more will be shipped,'' the judge said.
``The union will do all the work required of them, including
overtime if asked with no slowdowns and no sickouts.''
   His verbal order will be backed by a written decision in the
afternoon, Atkins said.
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said the groundings first
disclosed in court Wednesday have forced the airline ``to adjust the
schedules downward.'' He said passengers were being warned in
advance of any cancellations.
   ``Even the present backlog of grounded aircraft is totally
unacceptable and poses a severe threat to a company in Eastern's
dire financial condition,'' the Miami-based carrier wrote in its
court briefs.
   Wildcat walkouts earlier this month ``were overt acts of economic
warfare and tended to further the bargaining goals'' of the union,
the filing said.
   Russ McGarry, vice president of the Machinists' Miami local,
blamed the delays on management's actions in preparation for a
possible strike.
   ``We feel the company has purposely shipped out the parts,
shipped out equipment and depleted the number of personnel available
to work,'' McGarry said. ``They suspend a crew, then turn around and
farm out the work because there was nobody to do the job.''
   Eastern, a subsidiary of Houston-based Texas Air Corp., reported
losses estimated at $335.4 million for 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
