<FILEID>AP-NR-02-17-89 1315EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-TrailerTrain     02-17 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trailer Train,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>ICC Approves 5-Year Antitrust Exemption For Trailer Train</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Interstate Commerce Commission approved
today a 5-year antitrust exemption that allows a company owned by
major railroads to continue controlling rail car purchases.
   The company, Trailer Train Co. of Chicago, had asked for a
15-year extension over the objections of the Justice Department, the
state of Oregon and a major rail car builder. The commission imposed
some conditions on the arrangement and the final wording was being
worked out, said ICC spokesman Dennis Watson.
   The ICC gave the company an extension of a pooling arrangement
critics say amounts to a ``monopsony.'' This is an antitrust term
for a company that controls purchasing in an industry, often
enabling it to set prices and dictate product development.
   Trailer Train, which is owned by 22 railroads, controls about 80
percent of the nation's railroad flatcar fleet, including the vast
majority of intermodal cars, which are used to carry standardized
containers that also are loaded onto ships and trucks.
   ``The arrangement, including joint purchasing and ownershp of
rail cars, will be in the interest of better service to the public
and economy of operation, and will not unreasonably restrain
competition,'' the ICC said in its ruling.
   The company's pooling and leasing procedures allow railroads to
exchange cars so they can be used more efficiently and not have to
return empty.
   The commission also approved a proposed stock ownership
redistribution which extends ownership of Trailer Train to some
smaller railroads.
   Critics, including a company that has sold thousands of railcars
to Trailer Train, said prior to the decision that competition among
railcar suppliers will not survive if Trailer Train continues to
have control over purchasing for all of the nation's railroads.
   William A. Furman, president of Greenbrier Cos., whose subsidiary
Gunderson Inc. builds railcars in Oregon, said, ``Under these
current conditions, Trailer Train can, with government sanction,
abuse this tremendous economic power. We know they have abused it in
their dealings with us.''
   Furman noted that airlines are not allowed to pool together and
buy airplanes, ``nor can the railcar builders join together to
acquire raw materials, fix prices or allocate markets.''
   He said the number of companies building freight cars has fallen
from 20 in 1979 to four today.
   The Justice Department in November 1987 questioned Trailer
Train's antitrust immunity and asked the ICC to hold hearings and
reconsider before deciding whether to grant an extension. Today's
decision followed a 15-month investigation, including hearings
before an ICC administrative law judge.
   Oregon, whose pension fund has a 10 percent interest in
Gunderson, supported the Justice Department's action.
   The ICC approval, which takes effect in 30 days, is subject to
reconsideration if anyone can show the commission that the pooling
arrangement has not resulted in better service to the public or more
economic operation or has hindered competition, the commission said.
   The decision gives Trailer Train an antitrust exemption through
Sept. 30, 1994.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
