<FIRST>r f AM-Eastern-Gifts     02-17 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Gifts,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Shuttle Offering Gift Certificates To Passengers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern Machinists Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines, in its waning days as operator
of a Northeast air shuttle, is offering its shuttle passengers $50
department store gift certificates in a bid to lure fliers from Pan
Am Corp.'s rival service and keep its own passengers from defecting.
   Ailing Eastern started the promotion last month, a few weeks
after Pan Am started mailing its frequent shuttle passengers coupons
worth $25 off a one-way Pan Am shuttle ticket.
   The $50 Eastern certificates, redeemable at Bloomingdale's and
other well known department stores in the Northeast, are given to
passengers buying round-trip tickets. Two or more of the
certificates may be combined toward a purchase and certificates must
be redeemed by March 15.
   ``They (Eastern) are trying to hold the shuttle together,'' said
David Perelman, president of DMS Travel in New York. ``They're using
this as an incentive, as a bribe to keep people on the shuttle.''
   One-way shuttle fares are $99 during peak hours.
   Miami-based Eastern, which faces the threat of a possible strike
by its machinists union on March 3, also has introduced coupons for
the rest of its domestic system offering passengers big discounts if
they fly after that date.
   New York developer Donald Trump, who recently cleared a number of
regulatory hurdles, is scheduled to complete his $365 million
acquisition of the Eastern shuttle sometime next month.
   Eastern _ whose shuttle carries about 3 million passengers
annually _ and Pan Am are locked in fierce competition over their
lucrative shuttle services, which fly hourly between New York,
Boston and Washington and are used mainly by business travelers.
   Last week, Pan Am launched a new advertising campaign for its
shuttle service, calling it the ``Corporate Jet.'' Pan Am officials
denied that the new ad blitz was planned in anticipation of the
flamboyant Trump's debut as a competitor.
   But they conceded that curiosity and publicity about Trump will
prompt some passengers to take his shuttle service on a trial basis.
   Pan Am said its service now commands nearly 50 percent of the
Northeast shuttle market it shares with Eastern.
   The gift certificates are ``an attempt by Eastern to thank people
for their loyalty,'' Bruce Nobles, the head of the Eastern shuttle,
said in a telephone interview. He denied that the promotion was
designed to match Pan Am's flight credit coupons.
   Nobles formerly was president of the Pan Am shuttle and left
about a year ago to work for Eastern.
   ``We've really had a wonderful response (to the certificates); we
have seen an increase in customers on the shuttle,'' said Eastern
spokeswoman Cori Zywotow in Miami. She declined to specify the
increase in shuttle bookings which the airline attributes to the
certificate giveaway.
   The $50 certificates can be redeemed at Bloomingdale's and Macy's
in the New York area; Garfinckel's, Woodward &amp; Lothrop and
Bloomingdale's in Washington; and Filene's, Jordan Marsh and
Bloomingdale's in Boston.
</TEXT>
