<FIRST>r f AM-Italy-Maxwell     02-17 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Maxwell,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hints at Difficulties in Newspaper Startup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS REDMONT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British media baron Robert Maxwell canceled a major
address Friday on the launch of his English-language newspaper, The
European, saying his editorial team was not yet ``pursuing shared
goals and a unified concept.''
   The launch of the new daily, aiming to start with half a million
readers across Europe in early May, has already been postponed once.
   Maxwell, however, said in a last-minute letter in which he
withdrew as a keynote speaker at a European conference of Foreign
Press Associations that he had a ``total commitment to launching The
European as the first pan-European paper.''
   The 65-year-old Maxwell, who bought the U.S. publishing giant
Macmillan Inc. for $2.6 billion last fall, oversees a publishing
empire with operations in 28 countries and 40,000 employees.
   ``I would rather make sure this important project is right than
stick to a preconceived timetable and get it wrong,'' he said.
   ``Until I can be satisfied as publisher and editor-in-chief that
the English and French components of our editorial team are fully
and successfully integrated and pursuing shared goals and a unified
concept, I will not launch the paper,'' he added, saying he would
have another announcement next month.
   Maxwell immediately came under attack from participants at the
conference, aimed at setting the groundwork for better working
conditions for foreign correspondents around the world, particularly
in Europe.
   Eugenio Scalfari, editor of the Rome's largest circulation daily
La Repubblica, called the concept of The European ``a bestiality,''
adding that there was no such thing as European public opinion or
unified taste. He claimed that Maxwell was closing a printing plant
in France and firing some employees, reflecting difficulties in
starting such a newspaper.
   Scalfari supported the concept of national newspapers distributed
abroad, and challenged the Soviet Union to allow a newspaper owned
by Western Europeans to be printed in Moscow and distributed
throughout the country.
   The two-day conference, inaugurated by Italian President
Francesco Cossiga, also heard a proposal by the president of Italy's
state-owned television system to start a European newsfilm agency to
counteract American dominance of the field.
   The new Federation of Foreign Press Associations will seek to
avoid restrictions such as censorship and travel bans, and try to
limit physical harm to foreign correspondents around the world.
</TEXT>
