<HEAD>Convicted Insider Trader Talks To Ethics Students</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, Under tight... to CORRECT time element to
Thursday sted Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dennis B. Levine, the convicted Wall Street
insider trader whose exposure led to a major scandal, is briefing
business school students these days on the consequences of
white-collar crime.
   Under tight secrecy and a ban on reporters, Levine on Thursday
told a story of greed and power gone awry to about 90 Columbia
Business School students.
   ``He said it's very easy in such a heady exciting atmosphere
simply to lose yourself in the enormously competitive race,'' said
James Kuhn, who teaches ethics at Columbia and attended Levine's
speech. ``He now realizes it was a major source of his downfall.''
   Levine, 36, was paroled last year from a two-year jail term for
securities fraud, tax evasion and perjury. He had admitted making
$12.6 million in a five-year insider trading scheme by using
illegally obtained information about pending corporate takeovers.
   Levine's squealings led federal authorities to Ivan Boesky, the
now-imprisoned speculator who used illegal information peddled by
Levine to make millions himself.
   Dressed in a dark suit like the investment banker he once was,
Levine spoke for about 20 minutes at Columbia then answered student
questions for more than an hour, people in attendance said.
   He was brought to campus with the business school dean's approval
by a student group devoted to business ethics. Levine wasn't paid
for his appearance, Columbia officials said.
</TEXT>
