<FILEID>AP-NR-02-17-89 1508EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-AT&amp;TDecentralization     02-17 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AT&amp;T Decentralization,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>AT&amp;T To Decentralize; Focus On Business Units</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co., reorganizing
again, said Friday it would decentralize this year by giving more
power to the heads of 15 to 25 business units.
   The change should help the former phone monopoly focus on the
bottom line, but is likely to unsettle employees who have already
gone through several reorganizations since the 1984 breakup of the
Bell System, said Richard Toole, a Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. analyst.
   ``The old monopoly mentality is really being wrung out of the
company,'' Toole said. ``To another extent, you would like to get it
(the management structure) right, get it fixed once and for all.''
   The Wall Street Journal reported on the reorganization in a
Friday story based on an interview with Randall Tobias, an AT&amp;T vice
chairman. AT&amp;T did not officially announce the changes.
   ``More of the basic business decisions in the future will be made
by these individual business units rather than an overlay of top
corporate executives,'' said Walter Murphy, an AT&amp;T spokesman.
   ``There's not one big cutover date for this. It's all going to be
happening as the year rolls out,'' Murphy said. ``At a time when
things are going pretty well for us, this should make the company
perform even better.''
   The presidents of AT&amp;T's five major operating groups will be
renamed group executives and will oversee sets of business units
that will have direct responsibility for profits and losses, the
company said.
   The group executives will be Sam Willcoxon, in charge of
international activities; W. Frank Blount, communication products;
Victor A. Pelson, communication services; Robert M. Kavner,
computers; and E. Wayne Weeks, transmission and switching equipment.
</TEXT>
