<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet3pm     02-17 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0315</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices kept climbing today after a monthly
report on trade that came in close to expectations.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 14.11 to 2,325.54 by
3 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 5 to 3 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 894 up, 511 down and
515 unchanged.
   The Commerce Department reported this morning that the nation's
trade deficit narrowed to $11.89 billion in December from a revised
$12.22 billion the month before.
   The latest figure jibed with Wall Street estimates in the
neighborhood of $12 billion, although both exports and imports were
a bit stronger than expected.
   Analysts said the figures raised some concern that the Federal
Reserve might be inclined to tighten credit further.
   But they also noted a general sense of relief that the trade data
didn't contain any unpleasant surprises, as some talk on the Street
had suggested Thursday.
   Gainers among the blue chips included Eastman Kodak, up ~ at 48{;
DuPont, up ~ at 98}; McDonald's, up 1] at 51{; Procter &amp; Gamble, up
} at 91~, and General Electric, up 1[ at 47[.
   Navistar dropped ] to 5} in active trading. On Thursday the
company reported lower earnings for its fiscal quarter ended Jan. 31.
   Bank of New York rose 2 to 44, hitting a 52-week high. The
company said Thursday it expects annual earnings growth of 15
percent to 20 percent through 1991, somewhat more than its
historical targets.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks gained
.86 to 166.37. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .53 at 325.68.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 128.47 million shares with an
hour to go.
</TEXT>
