<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   02-17 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybeans Surge In Late Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices rallied higher Friday on
the Chicago Board of Trade as the market digested the day's bearish
news and adjusted to the reality of tight supplies. Grain futures
advanced modestly.
   The surge in soybean futures brought the market off its lowest
level this year. Earlier in the day, soybeans for delivery in March
had fallen to $7.22 a bushel on reports of steadily improving
growing conditions for the South American soybean crop.
   The Brazilian government had issued a report on Wednesday pegging
the 1988-89 Brazilian soybean crop at 22.6 million metric tons, an
increase from the 21.5 million to 22.1 million metric tons forecast
in December.
   The improved South American crop prospects have kept the soybean
market under pressure most of this month. But Friday's rally
suggested traders had refocused on the tight supply situation
created by last summer's drought.
   ``Everybody lost sight of the major point that there are very few
beans in the world at this point,'' said Cathy Leow, an analyst with
Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. in New York.
   At the close, wheat was \ cent lower to 2 cents higher with the
contract for March delivery at $4.24{ a bushel; corn was { cent to
2\ cents higher with March at $2.69{ a bushel; oats were 1{ cents to
3{ cents higher with March at $2.05} a bushel; soybeans were 10
cents to 20\ cents higher with March at $7.46 a bushel.
</TEXT>
